<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>Amended</UNDER> Notice of Appeal</TI>
<P>TAKE NOTICE THAT the Appellants appeal from the decision of the Honourable Justice David F. Hurley dated the 15<SUP>th</SUP> day of December, 2017 in proceedings in the Supreme Court of Newfoundland and Labrador Trial Division (General) bearing court number 2015 04 G 0120.</P>
<P>AND THAT the grounds of the proposed appeal are:</P>
<P>1. The Learned Judge committed a reviewable error by interpreting clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Appended as a Schedule to <EM>An Act for the Confirmation of an Agreement Between the Government and International Paper Company of Newfoundland Limited</EM> passed on September 6 [missing text]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> as taking away the Appellants' rights to litigate a claim in Court in favour of mandatory arbitration. In doing so, the Learned Judge contravened the modem approach to statutory interpretation, which instructs that the words contained in a statute are to be read in their entire context and in their grammatical and ordinary sense, harmoniously with the scheme and objects of the Act.</P>
<P>2. Clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement details the arbitration procedure for those scenarios for which arbitration has already been contemplated in the related legislation and agreements (&ldquo;Any questions, disputes or differences between the parties hereto, or between the Company and third parties <BOLD><UNDER>where provision for arbitration is made herein, or in the Act or Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements...&rdquo;)</UNDER></BOLD>. It does not expand the matters for which arbitration is mandatory. As the Learned Judge correctly concluded at paragraphs 26, 32, 35, 37 and 41, there is no provision in the 1915 legislation or 1923 legislation (or their related agreements) for mandatory arbitration that prohibits the Appellants' action in Court against the Respondent. Therefore the Learned Judge should have concluded that clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement does not require that the Appellants' matter be referred to arbitration.</P>
<P>3. The Learned Judge's interpretation of clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement defies the plain wording of the clause, which contains no expansion of the circumstances in which arbitration is mandatory.</P>
<P>4. The Learned Judge's reasons contain a significant inconsistency, finding correctly on the one hand that &ldquo;Clause 2(n) makes no reference to mandatory arbitration&rdquo; (para. 44) and then inconsistently concluding that &ldquo;Clause 2(n) mandated that both parties had to resort to arbitration&rdquo; (para. 46). The second conclusion is incorrect and is not supported by the wording of clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement, and leads the Learned Judge to commit a reviewable error.</P>
<P>5. The Learned Judge compounded this reviewable error by framing a party's right to commence a civil action as dependent upon a legislative provision conferring this right, rather than simply existing at common law. The Learned Judge characterized the &ldquo;Plaintiffs' right to initiate and maintain their action in Court&rdquo; as being a &ldquo;right granted in Section 14 of the <EM>1915 Act</EM>...&rdquo;. Respectfully, that is a significant mischaracterization of the common law that leads the Learned Judge to dismiss the Appellants' rights without an explicit legislative basis to do so.</P>
<P>6. The Learned Judge's conclusion not to exercise His Lordship's discretion to deny the application for a stay is based upon His Lordship's reviewable error that there is a legislative basis to deny the Appellants' right to maintain an action in Court. The Learned Judge committed further reviewable errors in this regard by failing to address the advantages of civil litigation&mdash;economic and judicial efficiencies, promotion of access to justice&mdash;over arbitration. The Learned Judge also committed a reviewable error by failing to address the fact that arbitration is ill-suited to deal with the complex causation questions that arise in this case and which necessitate judicial consideration of expert evidence.</P>
<P>7. The Learned Judge committed a further reviewable error by failing to require that the Respondent put before the Court sufficient evidence that the Respondent is a successor company of the International Paper Company of Newfoundland, Limited, the signatory to the 1927 Agreement.</P>
<P>8. Such further and other grounds as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P>
<P>AND THAT the Appellants will request that the decision appealed from be reversed.</P>
<P><UNDER>DATED AT Halifax, Nova Scotia, this 1<SUP>st</SUP> day of May, 2018.</UNDER></P>
