<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>PART I: OVERVIEW</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. The Appellants commenced a proposed class action against five Defendants on May 22, 2015. Comer Brook Pulp and Paper Limited is one of the Defendants, and for the purposes of this Factum will be referred to as the Respondent to this appeal.
<P1>Statement of Claim issued May 22, 2015 [Appeal Book, Tab 4, Page 26].</P1></P>
<P>2. Before a hearing of the application for certification of the proposed class action, the Respondent brought an application to stay the proposed class action on the basis that the Appellants are, purportedly, obligated by historical legislation to resolve the dispute, <EM>vis-&ag;-vis</EM> the Respondent, through arbitration (the &ldquo;Jurisdiction Application&rdquo;). The Jurisdiction Application was opposed by the Appellants, as well as by the Town of Deer Lake and the Province of Newfoundland and Labrador.
<P1>Memorandum of Fact and Law of the Plaintiffs (Appellants). Jurisdiction Application [Appeal Book, Tab 11, Page 123].</P1>
<P1>Memorandum of Fact and Law of the Town of Deer Lake, Jurisdiction Application [Appeal Book. Tab 12, Page 150].</P1>
<P1>Memorandum of Fact and Law of the Her Majesty the Queen in Right of Newfoundland and Labrador, Jurisdiction Application [Appeal Book, Tab 13, Page 172].</P1></P>
<P>3. The Jurisdiction Application was granted by the Honourable Justice Hurley of the Supreme Court of Newfoundland and Labrador by way of a decision dated December 15, 2017 (the &ldquo;Decision&rdquo;). The Decision forms the basis of the present appeal.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Dewey v. Kruger Inc.</SOC><CITE>2017 NLTD(G) 203</CITE></CASEREF>, December 15, 2017 (&ldquo;Decision&rdquo;) [Appeal Book, Tab 3, Page 8].</P1></P>
<P>4. In allowing the Respondent's Jurisdiction Application, the Learned Judge contravened the modem approach to statutory interpretation, which instructs that the words contained in a statute are to be read in their entire context and in their grammatical and ordinary sense, harmoniously with the scheme of the Act and the objects of the Act.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Rizzo &amp; Rizzo Shoes Ltd. (Re)</SOC><CITE>[1998] 1 S.C.R. 27</CITE><PARANUM>21</PARANUM></CASEREF> [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 7].</P1></P>
<P>5. Respectfully, there is no basis in the statute relied on by the Learned Judge <EM>(An Act for the Confirmation of an Agreement Between the Government and International Paper Company of Newfoundland, Limited</EM>, Cap. 4, 18 Geo. v. (1927), passed on September 6, 1927 (the &ldquo;<EM>192</EM>7 <EM>Act</EM>&rdquo;)) to override the procedural right of the Appellants to bring a civil action for damages. The Learned Judge's interpretation of the legislation defies the plain wording of the 1927 Agreement (appended to the 1927 Act); specifically, clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement.
<P1><EM>1927 Act</EM> [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 12].</P1></P>
<P>6. The Learned Judge compounded this reversible error in statutory interpretation by framing the right to commence a civil action as being dependent upon legislation positively granting this right, rather than the right existing at common law. The Learned Judge characterized the &ldquo;Plaintiffs' right to initiate and maintain their action in Court&rdquo; as being a &ldquo;right granted in Section 14 of the <EM>1915 Act</EM>...&rdquo;. Respectfully, that is a significant mischaracterization of the common law, a mischaracterization that subsequently informs the Learned Judge's dismissal&mdash;with no legislative basis to do sol&mdash;of the Appellants' rights to commence an action.
<P1>Decision, para. 41 [Appeal Book, Tab 3, Page 20].</P1></P>
<P>7. In addition, it was a reversible error for the Learned Judge to exercise his discretionary power to deny the stay&mdash;which, it is submitted, was not a discretionary decision even available to His Lordship, given there was no legislative basis to compel arbitration in the first place. In so doing, the Learned Judge relied upon irrelevant jurisprudence.</P>
<P>8. For these primary reasons, as more fully described below, and for the additional reasons outlined herein, the Appellants respectfully submit that the Decision should be overturned and the Jurisdiction Application denied.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II"><UNDER>PART II: CONCISE STATEMENT OF FACTS</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>Overview of the Class Action</TI>
<P>9. The proposed class action has been commenced by four representative plaintiffs on behalf of a class of property owners within a defined area of the Town of Deer Lake, in the province of Newfoundland and Labrador.</P>
<P>10. The property owners allege flooding of, and water damage to, their properties. The Statement of Claim alleges that the Defendants, including the Respondent, are liable for this damage due to their respective roles in, <EM>inter alia</EM>, creating and overseeing a water control system constructed for the production of hydroelectric power. The water control system includes a reservoir (Grand Lake Reservoir), a series of dams and dykes, and the man-made Humber Canal (collectively, the &ldquo;Water Control System&rdquo;). It is alleged that water seeps from the Water Control System, causing elevated groundwater levels and extensive water damage to properties and grounds, in turn rendering the properties unfit for habitation.</P>
<P>11. Through the vehicle of a proposed class action, the Appellants seek, on their own behalf and on behalf of the Class, <EM>inter alia</EM> damages for interference with their property rights.</P>
<P>12. Nuisance and negligence are alleged against the Respondent. As against the non-Kruger-associated Defendants (that is, the Town of Deer Lake and the Province of Newfoundland and Labrador), the Appellants allege negligence.</P>
<P>13. At the time of filing this Factum, no defence to the Statement of Claim has been filed by any Defendant to the proceeding.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>The Jurisdiction Application and Decision</TI>
<P>14. The first case management meeting was conducted on February 8. 2016. At the case management meeting, the Court scheduled the hearing of an application to determine the sequence of the Jurisdiction Application (the subject of the present appeal) and the application for certification of the proposed class action. The Appellants had argued that the jurisdiction issue ought to be determined at the same time as the hearing of the certification application, to avoid the delay of inserting an additional hearing (and potential appeal therefrom) prior to the first major procedural step of certification.</P>
<P>15. This separate application to determine the sequence of the Jurisdiction Application and certification application was heard on March 10, 2016 (the &ldquo;Timing Application&rdquo;). A decision in the Timing Application was rendered by the Honourable Justice Hurley on June 17, 2016. His Lordship ordered the Jurisdiction Application to be heard in advance of the certification application.</P>
<P>16. The Jurisdiction Application was heard by the Learned Judge on December 7, 2016. It was opposed by the Appellants, the Town of Deer Lake and the Province. Kruger Inc. and Deer Lake Power Company did not participate.</P>
<P>17. By the Decision dated December 15, 2017. the Learned Judge allowed the application by the Respondent to stay the proceeding against it in the Court. The Learned Judge concluded that the parties opposing the Jurisdiction Application&mdash;the Appellants, the Province and the Town&mdash;had not established that the Court &ldquo;should not follow the legislation which provides that the questions, disputes or differences between the Plaintiffs and Comer Brook Pulp &amp; Paper Limited be referred to arbitration.&rdquo;
<P1>Decision, para. 61 [Appeal Book, Tab 3, Page 25].</P1></P>
<P>18. The Appellants disagree with the Learned Judge's conclusion that the legislation provides that questions, disputes or differences between the Plaintiffs and the Respondent must be referred to arbitration. The Learned Judge based his conclusion specifically on a clause in an agreement appended to the 1927 Act.
<P1><EM>1927 Act</EM> [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 12].</P1></P>
<P>19. The Learned Judge reviewed various provisions in three historical statutes starting in 1915 and ending in 1927:
<P1>i. <EM>An Act for the Confirmation of a Contract with the Newfoundland Products Corporation, Limited</EM>, Cap. 4, 6 Geo. v. (1915) (the &ldquo;1915 Act&rdquo;). The 1915 Act approved and confirmed an attached indenture agreement entered into between the Government and the Newfoundland Products Corporation, Limited (the &ldquo;1915 Agreement&rdquo;).
<P2>Appellants' Authorities, Tab 10.</P2></P1>
<P1>ii. <EM>An Act Further to Amend the Act 6 George V. (1915), Chapter Four, Entitled &ldquo;An Act for the Confirmation of a Contract with the Newfoundland Products Corporation, Limited</EM>&rdquo;, Cap. 1, 14 Geo. v. (1923) (the &ldquo;1923 Act&rdquo;). The 1923 Act amends various sections of the 1915 Act, and sets out the terms of the financial arrangement between the parties. It attaches, and approves and confirms, two agreements, constituting Part I and Part II of the Schedule to the 1923 Act (the &ldquo;1923 Agreements&rdquo;). These agreements are themselves to further amend the 1915 Agreement and the 1915 Act.
<P2>Appellants' Authorities, Tab 11.</P2></P1>
<P1>iii. <EM>An Act for the Confirmation of an Agreement Between the Government and International Paper Company of Newfoundland, Limited</EM>, Cap. 4, 18 Geo. v. (1927). The title of the 1927 Act itself explains its object: to confirm an agreement entered into between the two signatory parties on August 2, 1927 (the &ldquo;1927 Agreement&rdquo;, appended as a schedule to the 1927 Act).
<P2>Appellant's Authorities, Tab 12.</P2></P1></P>
<P>20. The Respondent was unable to identify any recent legislation or agreements purporting to refer to mandatory arbitration claims of the nature asserted by the Appellants. Instead, it relied on this historical legislation. There was no evidence to support any claims having ever been submitted to an arbitration process such as that outlined in the legislation.
<P1>Transcript of the Hearing of the Jurisdiction Application (&ldquo;Transcript&rdquo;), pg. 11, lines 1&ndash;10 [Appeal Book, Tab 7, Page 56].</P1></P>
<P>21. The Learned Judge commenced his review of the legislation with the 1915 Act. The Learned Judge concluded that arbitration of disputes was <EM>not</EM> mandated by that particular Act. At paragraph 10 of the Decision, the Learned Judge concluded that &ldquo;a review of the legislation supports the position that Claimants under the legislation at that point in time maintained the right to pursue their claim in Court without being restricted to arbitration.&rdquo;
<P1>Decision, paras. 10, 26 [Appeal Book, Tab 3, Pages 13 and 16].</P1></P>
<P>22. The Learned Judge subsequently reviewed the 1923 and 1927 legislation.</P>
<P>23. With respect to the 1923 legislation, the Learned Judge agreed with the Appellants that neither the 1923 Agreement nor Part I of the Schedule to the 1923 Act contained any relevant provisions requiring reference of the claims to arbitration.
<P1>Decision, para. 34 [Appeal Book, Tab 3, Page 18].</P1></P>
<P>24. With respect to Part II of the Schedule to the 1923 Act, the Learned Judge also accepted the Appellants' position that Clause 8 did not alter the right of a claimant to initiate or pursue a claim in Court.
<P1>Decision, para. 37 [Appeal Book, Tab 3, Page 19].</P1></P>
<P>25. The Learned Judge's decision to grant the stay was based on one provision: clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement. This was also the provision primarily relied on by the Respondent (though it had argued that the preceding provisions also compelled arbitration).
<P1>Decision, para. 40 [Appeal Book, Tab 3, Pages 19 and 20].</P1></P>
<P>26. Clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement provides the following:
<QUOTE><P>Clause 8 of the Agreement of 1923 shall not apply to the Company: but the following provision shall apply to the Company:
<QUOTE><P>Any questions, disputes or differences between the parties hereto, or between the Company and third parties <BOLD><UNDER>where provision for arbitration is made herein, or in the Act or Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements</UNDER>,</BOLD> arising out of, under or in connection with this Agreement or the Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements, or the execution thereof, shall on the application of either party be submitted to the arbitration of three arbitrators and the provisions of Part VI. of the Judicature Act, Chapter 83 of the Consolidated Statutes (Third Series), except Section 212 and except as modified in this Clause, shall apply to any such submission. One arbitrator shall be appointed by each of the parties and the third by the two so appointed. If either party does not appoint an arbitrator within twenty days after request in writing from the other party, or if the two arbitrators do not appoint the third within twenty days of the appointment of the second of such two, the Supreme Court or a Judge thereof may upon application by either party appoint such arbitrator orarbitrators. The award of the arbitrators or any two of them shall be final and binding upon the parties thereto, unless appeal therefrom shall be made to the Supreme Court and notice of such appeal shall be filed in the Registry of the Supreme Court within thirty days from the date of such award. [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>27. The wording of clause 2(n) of the 1927Agreement does not require arbitration of the Appellants' claims, for the reasons that will be outlined in this Factum.</P>
<P>28. Further, the Learned Judge respectfully demonstrates an error in his preliminary comments on the effect of clause 2(n). The Learned Judge states at paragraph 41 of the Decision:
<QUOTE><P>The parties generally conceded that the Plaintiffs' right to initiate and maintain their action in Court depended upon the proper interpretation of that Clause. <BOLD><UNDER>As well it was generally accepted that the 1915 legislation gave claimants this right.</UNDER></BOLD> Contrary to the argument put forth by the Company [Respondent], I found that this right granted in Section 14 of the 1915 Act was not changed by legislation passed in 1923.</P>
<P>In my opinion, the 1927 legislation removed the rights of the claimants such as the Plaintiffs to pursue their claim in Court as originally provided in Section 14 of the 1915 Act. [...] [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>29. These preliminary comments contain an incorrect premise that a claimant (such as the Plaintiffs) must by legislation be &ldquo;given a right&rdquo; to initiate an action in Court. In this particular case he states that Section 14 of the 1915 Act gives the claimants the right to litigate in Court:
<QUOTE><P>As well, it was generally accepted that the 1915 legislation <UNDER>gave claimants this right</UNDER> [to initiate and maintain their action in Court].</P>
<P>[underline added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Decision, para. 41 [Appeal Book, Tab 3, Page 20].</P1></P>
<P>30. This is incorrect. The Appellants, like all litigants, have a right to initiate an action in court&mdash;whether by way of a proposed class action or otherwise&mdash;that is not predicated on, or dependent upon, any legislative grant of such a right.</P>
<P>31. Absent <UNDER>express</UNDER> language to the contrary, in legislation or in a binding agreement between the relevant parties, the Appellants have a right to initiate an action in Court.</P>
<P>32. The Learned Judge's faulty reasoning&mdash;that there is no right to initiate and maintain an action in Court except if legislation <EM>grants</EM> such a right&mdash;sets the stage for a subsequent interpretation of the legislation that fails to identify express language excluding that right.</P>
<P>33. Having framed the right to initiate an action in Court as being dependent upon a positive granting of such right in Section 14 of the 1915 Act, the Learned Judge subsequently says that &ldquo;While Clause 2(n) does not explicitly refer to Section 14 of the 1915 Act, the matters set out in that clause [clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement] effectively take away the right to litigate a claim in Court in favour of mandatory arbitration.&rdquo;
<P1>Decision, para. 42 [Appeal Book, Tab 3, Page 20].</P1></P>
<P>34. The conclusion that the common law right to start an action has &ldquo;effectively&rdquo; been taken away is, with respect, unsupported by the legislation, and is not the correct test in assessing whether the right to litigate has been ousted by legislation. There is no rigour to the Learned Judge's interpretation. &ldquo;Effectively&rdquo; taking away a right is, with respect, not the proper legal test.</P>
<P>35. As stated by Mr. Wagner, Q.C., counsel for the Appellants, at the hearing of the Jurisdiction Application:
<QUOTE><P>Previous legislation does not automatically become obsolete unless specifically stated in the subsequent legislation. That is a reversal of the way of legislative amendments. The older provisions remain in effect except where they're amended.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Transcript, p. 79. lines 5&ndash;10 [Appeal Book, Tab 7, Page 62].</P1></P>
<P>36. Nothing in the legislation amends, changes or revokes the Appellants' rights to initiate an action, which are in fact <UNDER>expressly preserved</UNDER> by Section 14 of the 1915 Act. as the Learned Judge acknowledged.</P>
<P>37. Critical to the intended meaning of clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement is the following wording: &ldquo;...where provision for arbitration is made herein, or in the Act or Agreement of 1915 of any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements [...].&rdquo; This portion of the clause cannot be ignored or taken out of context. It provides the parameters of clause 2(n). The clause is modifying the arbitration <EM>procedure</EM> to be followed in instances <EM>where provision for arbitration is made</EM>. The Learned Judge fails to ascribe plain and ordinary meaning to the language of clause 2(n). He elides the language of clause 2(n) with the following statement: &ldquo;The various clauses and provisions relating to claims and in particular Clause 15 of the 1915 Agreement contain an optional provision for arbitration which can be chosen by the claimants. The fact that a claimant could opt to initiate a claim in Court does not mean that there was no provision for arbitration.&rdquo;
<P1>Decision, paras. 44, 45 [Appeal Book, Tab 3, Page 21].</P1></P>
<P>38. In this statement, the Learned Judge has equated an <EM>option</EM> for arbitration with a <EM>mandatory</EM> arbitration process. He has imposed mandatory arbitration on the Plaintiffs' claims without the legislative basis to do so.</P>
<P>39. The Learned Judge makes no mention of a need for <EM>explicit</EM> language removing the right to initiate civil action. Indeed the Learned Judge does not apply this necessary, rigorous requirement to his assessment. The Decision contains no reconciliation of his decision to grant the stay with the language of clause 2(n), and to the need to have explicit language overriding the right to initiate an action in court. Further, the Learned Judge contradicts himself in concluding on the one hand:
<QUOTE><P>[...] Clause 2(n) makes <UNDER>no reference</UNDER> to mandatory arbitration.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Decision, para. 44 [Appeal Book, Tab 3, Page 21].</P1></P>
<P>And on the other:
<QUOTE><P>Section 14 gave the option of arbitration or Court to a claimant, while Clause 2(n) <UNDER>mandated</UNDER> that both parties had to resort to arbitration.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Decision, para. 46 [Appeal Book, Tab 3, Page 21].</P1></P>
<P>40. The latter statement is entirely unsupported by the Learned Judge's preceding assessment, has no basis in the legislation, and contradicts his correct interpretation two paragraphs earlier that clause 2(n) makes no reference to mandatory arbitration. Again, clause 2(n) simply modifies the arbitration procedure to be followed <EM>when</EM> arbitration is being conducted. It is not in itself sufficient, or intended, to compel arbitration.</P>
<P>41. Subsequently the Learned Judge, having concluded at paragraph 48 that &ldquo;there has been finding for mandatory arbitration&rdquo;, considered whether he ought to exercise discretion to nevertheless deny the stay of proceedings against the Respondent.</P>
<P>42. The Learned Judge's ensuing analysis of his discretionary power is fundamentally flawed, because it is predicated on his conclusion that arbitration is mandated by the legislation. For the reasons outlined above and further detailed Part IV of this Factum, that conclusion is unsupported by the legislation.</P>
<P>43. In addition to that fundamental error, the Learned Judge reviews jurisprudence of the Supreme Court of Canada which, he concludes, &ldquo;has consistently held in a number of recent decisions that the presence of a mandatory arbitration clause precludes the Courts from having jurisdiction to determine the matter.&rdquo;
<P1>Decision, para. 52 [Appeal Book, Tab 3, Page 22].</P1></P>
<P>44. The Learned Judge's analysis of his discretionary power is premised on his equivalence of the present matter with jurisprudence in which legislation or a contract, as the case may be, clearly mandated arbitration in the circumstances at hand. That was the context for those cases, setting up the question about whether, despite the clearly mandated arbitration, there was a reason not to apply the legislation or commercial contract agreed to by the parties. At play in the jurisprudence relied upon by the Learned Judge are established policy reasons to uphold the autonomy of parties, preserve commercial certainty, and respect labour relations principles. The findings in these cases cannot be applied to the present case.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>Notice of Appeal</TI>
<P>45. In the Notice of Appeal, the following grounds of appeal are set out. As outlined in Part III (List of the Issues), these will be combined for purposes of this Factum into two main issues.
<P1>1. The Learned Judge committed a reviewable error by interpreting clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement as taking away the Appellants' rights to litigate a claim in Court in favour of mandatory arbitration. In doing so. the Learned Judge contravened the modem approach to statutory interpretation, which instructs that the words contained in a statute are to be read in their entire context and in their grammatical and ordinary sense, harmoniously with the scheme and objects of the Act.</P1>
<P1>2. Clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement details the arbitration procedure for those scenarios for which arbitration has already been contemplated in the related legislation and agreements (&ldquo;Any questions, disputes or differences between the parties hereto, or between the Company and third parties <BOLD><UNDER>where provision for arbitration is made herein, or in the Act or Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements...&rdquo;)</UNDER></BOLD>. It does not expand the matters for which arbitration is mandatory. As the Learned Judge correctly concluded at paragraphs 26, 32, 35, 37 and 41, there is no provision in the 1915 legislation or 1923 legislation (or their related agreements) for mandatory arbitration that prohibits the Appellants' action in Court against the Respondent. Therefore the Learned Judge should have concluded that clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement does not require that the Appellants' matter be referred to arbitration.</P1>
<P1>3. The Learned Judge's interpretation of clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement defies the plain wording of the clause, which contains no expansion of the circumstances in which arbitration is mandatory.</P1>
<P1>4. The Learned Judge's reasons contain a significant inconsistency, finding correctly on the one hand that &ldquo;Clause 2(n) makes no reference to mandatory arbitration&rdquo; (para. 44) and then inconsistently concluding that &ldquo;Clause 2(n) mandated that both parties had to resort to arbitration&rdquo; (para. 46). The second conclusion is incorrect and is not supported by the wording of clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement, and leads the Learned Judge to commit a reviewable error.</P1>
<P1>5. The Learned Judge compounded this reviewable error by framing a party's right to commence a civil action as dependent upon a legislative provision conferring this right, rather than simply existing at common law. The Learned Judge characterized the &ldquo;Plaintiffs' right to initiate and maintain their action in Court&rdquo; as being a &ldquo;right granted in Section 14 of the <EM>1915 Act</EM>...&rdquo;. Respectfully, that is a significant mischaracterization of the common law that leads the Learned Judge to dismiss the Appellants' rights without an explicit legislative basis to do so.</P1>
<P1>6. The Learned Judge's conclusion not to exercise His Lordship's discretion to deny the application for a stay is based upon His Lordship's reviewable error that there is a legislative basis to deny the Appellants' right to maintain an action in Court. The Learned Judge committed further reviewable errors in this regard by failing to address the advantages of civil litigation&mdash;economic and judicial efficiencies, promotion of access to justice&mdash;over arbitration. The Learned Judge also committed a reviewable error by failing to address the fact that arbitration is ill-suited to deal with the complex causation questions that arise in this case and which necessitate judicial consideration of expert evidence.</P1>
<P1>7. The Learned Judge committed a further reviewable error by failing to require that the Respondent put before the Court sufficient evidence that the Respondent is a successor company of the International Paper Company of Newfoundland, Limited, the signatory to the 1927 Agreement.
<P2>Amended Notice of Appeal issued May 2, 2018 [Appeal Book, Tab 2, Page 4].</P2></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III: LIST OF THE ISSUES</TI>
<P>46. There are two main issues:
<P1>a) Did the Learned Judge commit reversible errors in failing to apply the proper principles of statutory interpretation, and in so doing, concluding that clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement compelled arbitration of the Appellants' claims?</P1>
<P1>b) Did the Learned Judge commit a reversible error by declining to exercise discretion to dismiss the Jurisdiction Application?</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV: ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>Standard of Review</TI>
<P>47. The first issue on appeal asks whether arbitration was compelled by the legislation relied on by the Respondent. It is an issue of pure statutory interpretation.</P>
<P>48. Statutory interpretation may generally be viewed as a question of mixed fact and law, as the modem approach to statutory interpretation dictates a contextual approach to interpretation.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Midnight Marine Ltd. v. Oppenheim</SOC><CITE>2010 NLCA 64</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>302 Nfld. &amp; P.E.I.R. 85</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>NLCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> paras. 33 to 37 [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 5].</P1></P>
<P>49. However, the appropriate standard of review does not automatically become one of palpable and overriding error (as applies to questions of mixed fact and law) in every case involving interpretation of a statute. As noted by the Court in <EM>Midnight Marine</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, if a decision-maker omits to consider a relevant factor such as the precise wording of a text, the decision-maker in effect applies the wrong law, and this amounts to an error of law, reviewable on the more exacting correctness standard.</P>
<P>50. The present case is one of pure statutory interpretation. There were no findings of fact made by the Learned Judge and there was not a factual record providing context for interpretation of the legislation; rather the legislation itself was the only material considered.
<P1><EM>Midnight Marine</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, para. 44 [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 5].</P1></P>
<P>51. At the hearing of the Jurisdiction Application, the Learned Judge asked counsel for the parties whether his task was to determine a question of law. There was consensus that yes, it was.
<P1>Transcript, p. 38 at lines 3&ndash;25; p. 39 at lines 1&ndash;16; p. 113 at lines 23- 25: p. 114 at lines 1&ndash;20 [Appeal Book, Tab 7, Pages 60 and 63].</P1></P>
<P>52. The governing standard of review for questions of law is set out by the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Housen v. Nikolaisen</SOC></CASEREF> at paragraph 8:
<QUOTE><P>On a pure question of law, the basic rule with respect to the review of a trial judge's findings is that an appellate court is free to replace the opinion of the trial judge with its own. Thus the standard of review on a question of law is that of correctness [citation omitted].</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Housen v. Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 33</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2002] 2 S.C.R. 235</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>, para. 8 [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 2].</P1></P>
<P>53. The applicable standard of review for issue one is correctness.</P>
<P>54. The second issue concerns an exercise of discretion. The Appellants maintain that it was not open to the Learned Judge to consider the question of discretion (as arbitration was not mandated by the legislation), and it was an error in law to do so. reviewable on a standard of correctness. Had the question of discretion been properly before the Learned Judge, however, the applicable standard of review would reflect a degree of deference and be one of palpable and overriding error, unless the error amounted to an error of law, which would be subject to a standard of correctness.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>The Modern Approach to Statutory Interpretation</TI>
<P>55. The Jurisdiction Application boiled down to a question of statutory interpretation; specifically, how to properly interpret the legislation relied upon by the Respondent. The purported arbitration clauses are contained in historical statutes that, largely, serve to confirm agreements concluded between the years of 1915 and 1927 by the Government of Newfoundland (as it was then known) and various companies. If the Applicant (Respondent) was to succeed in its Jurisdiction Application, the Court had to be satisfied that this historical legislation, properly interpreted, ousts the Appellants' procedural rights to seek to resolve the dispute against the Respondent by way of a proposed class action.</P>
<P>56. The modem approach to statutory interpretation instructs that the words contained in a statute are to be read in their entire context and in their grammatical and ordinary sense, harmoniously with the scheme of the Act and the objects of the Act.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Rizzo &amp; Rizzo Shoes Ltd. (Re)</SOC><CITE>[1998] 1 S.C.R. 27</CITE><PARANUM>21</PARANUM></CASEREF> [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 7].</P1></P>
<P>57. The modem approach to statutory interpretation is consistent with section 16 of the <EM>Interpretation Act</EM>, R.S.N.L. 1990, c. I-19 (the &ldquo;Interpretation Act&rdquo;), which mandates an interpretive approach as follows:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>16.</N><TI>Rule of construction</TI><SECP>Every Act and every regulation and every provision of an Act or regulation shall be considered remedial and shall receive the liberal construction and interpretation that best ensures the attainment of the objects of the Act, regulation, or provision according to its true meaning.</SECP></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1>Interpretation Act [Appellant's Authorities, Tab 13].</P1>
<P1>Also see, for e.g., <CASEREF><SOC>Newfoundland and Labrador (Attorney General) v. Newfoundland and Labrador (Information and Privacy Commissioner)</SOC><CITE>2011 NLCA 69</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>314 Nfld. &amp; P.E.I.R. 305</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> at paras. 25-26 [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 6]</P1></P>
<P>58. In <CASEREF><SOC>Archean Resources Ltd v. Newfoundland (Minister of Finance)</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court of Appeal provided guidance for determining the &ldquo;true meaning&rdquo; of legislation. Green J.A., as he then was, explained the following:
<QUOTE><P>[22] Instead of mandating some fictionalized search for a collective &ldquo;legislative intention&rdquo;, s. 16 directs the court to consider every provision &ldquo;remedial&rdquo; and to interpret it so that it &ldquo;best&rdquo; ensures the attainment of its &ldquo;objects&rdquo; according to its &ldquo;true&rdquo; meaning. This requires a consideration, as an integral part of the interpretive exercise, of the problem or &ldquo;mischief&rdquo; to which the legislature directed its legislative act as a remedy and then the drawing of an inference, based on the language of the whole enactment and the court's general knowledge of the state of the pre-existing law and any information as to the broad social context in which the legislative act occurred, as to what, broadly speaking, the object or objects of the legislative act must have been. The end result is to arrive at a &ldquo;true&rdquo; meaning. That inevitably requires an examination of more than the bare words of the legislative enactment that is in issue, no matter how clear or unambiguous they may at first blush appear. The surrounding text, the interrelation of other related statutes, the social and legislative context in which the provision was enacted, and other extrinsic aids are all sources to be consulted in this exercise. Obviously, if the bare words of the relevant provision appear to be straightforward and seem on their face to admit of only one meaning, they may end up controlling the result, but even in such a case, it is not sufficient to stop the interpretive exercise at this &ldquo;plain&rdquo; meaning; s. 16 requires that at the very least this plain meaning be given a &ldquo;reality check&rdquo; by being tested against other relevant sources of meaning to ensure that there is not some nuance or variation in the normal or apparent meaning that might indicate a different meaning in the particular context under consideration. &ldquo;True&rdquo; meaning is not plain meaning; it is a conclusion arrived at by reconciling all the appropriate indicators of meaning that the court is directed to consider.</P>
<P>[23] In truth therefore, s. 16 enunciates a principle of harmonization in which the courts are directed, in cases of dispute, to adopt and apply an interpretation that fairly reconciles the language used in the enactment with the broader objects of the legislation so as to achieve the general goal, or to rectify the mischief, to which the legislative act appears to have been directed. That exercise determines the general ambit of impact of the legislative act and provides the basis for the court to conclude whether the particular fact situation before it should fall inside or outside that ambit.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>2002 NFCA 43, 215 Nfld. &amp; P.E.I.R. 124 at paras. 22-23 [Appellants' Authorities. Tab 1].</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>ISSUE ONE</TI>
<P><P1><EM>Did the Learned Judge commit reversible errors in failing to apply the proper principles of statutory interpretation, and in so doing, concluding that clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement compelled arbitration of the Appellants' claims?</EM></P1></P>
<BLOCK4><N>i.</N><TI>Absent express language to the contrary, the right to commence an action in Court is not removed</TI>
<P>59. It is trite law that absent express language to the contrary, in legislation or in a binding agreement, a claimant has the right to initiate a claim in court.</P>
<P>60. The Learned Judge's conclusion that the common law right to start an action has &ldquo;effectively&rdquo; been taken away is, with respect, unsupported by the legislation, and is not the correct test in assessing whether the right to litigate has been removed by legislation. &ldquo;Effectively&rdquo; taking away a right is not the correct legal test to apply.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>ii.</N><TI>Language of clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement does not support Learned Judge's interpretation</TI>
<P>61. As detailed above, the clause primarily relied upon by the Respondent, and relied upon by the Learned Judge in reaching his conclusion to grant the stay, is contained in clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement appended to the 1927 Act.
<P1>Appellants' Authorities, Tab 12.</P1></P>
<P>62. It should be noted that the entire Jurisdiction Application brought by the Respondent was premised on the unestablished fact of the Respondent &ldquo;stepping into the shoes&rdquo; of, and assuming the rights and obligations of, the International Paper Company of Newfoundland, Limited (the &ldquo;Second Company&rdquo;), the signatory to this 1927 Agreement. There was no evidence put before the Learned Judge that the Respondent is the successor company of the Second Company, although this is implied by the Respondent's position and was not challenged by the Learned Judge. In the Appellants' respectful view, this is not an insignificant factual question.</P>
<P>63. The title of the 1927 Act itself explains its object: to confirm an agreement entered into between the two signatory parties on August 2, 1927 (the &ldquo;1927 Agreement&rdquo;, appended as a schedule to the 1927 Act). Section 1 of the 1927 Act underscores this object, providing that the 1927 Agreement is &ldquo;approved, confirmed and adopted&rdquo; and shall &ldquo;have the force and effect of law&rdquo;.</P>
<P>64. The object of the 1927 Agreement is also confirmed by its recitals, which explain that the Second Company is to acquire the property and assets of Newfoundland Power and Paper Company, Limited (the &ldquo;First Company&rdquo;), and as such it essentially steps into the shoes of the First Company with respect to several agreements between the Government and the First Company, whereby the First Company was granted certain rights, powers and privileges in exchange for certain obligations. The 1927 Agreement provides that the Government continues to act as guarantor of instruments of the Second Company and is entitled to certain taxes and import duties paid by the Second Company.</P>
<P>65. The 1927 Act also serves to confirm and amend older agreements, all of which together relate to the same topic&mdash;arrangements between the Government and related companies. As directed by the Court of Appeal in <EM>Arche an</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, the object of these interrelated statutes (to which the older agreements are annexed) will be considered as context.</P>
<P>66. The first of these interrelated statutes was passed on June 5, 1915. This is <EM>An Act for the Confirmation of a Contract with the Newfoundland Products Corporation, Limited</EM> (the &ldquo;1915 Act&rdquo;). Like the 1927 Act, it approved and confirmed an attached indenture agreement entered into between the Government and the Newfoundland Products Corporation, Limited (the &ldquo;1915 Agreement&rdquo;). The recitals of the 1915 Agreement provide, <EM>inter alia</EM>, that the Newfoundland Products Corporation, Limited has been incorporated &ldquo;for the purpose chiefly of developing certain waters for the manufacture of fertilizers and such other articles and substances in connection with the Company's business&rdquo;.
<P1>1915 Act [Appellants' Authorities. Tab 10].</P1>
<P1>Recitals. 1915 Agreement [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 10].</P1></P>
<P>67. The 1915 Agreement further provides that in connection therewith the Government has demised to it &ldquo;the water power or powers in and upon the Humber River, and in and upon Junction Brook&rdquo; and associated rights and privileges.
<P1>Clause 1, 1915 Agreement [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 10].</P1></P>
<P>68. On July 13, 1923, <EM>An Act Further to Amend the Act 6 George V. (1915), Chapter Four, Entitled &ldquo;An Act for the Confirmation of a Contract with the Newfoundland Products Corporation, Limited&rdquo;</EM> (the &ldquo;1923 Act&rdquo;) was enacted. As its recitals set out, the Newfoundland Products Corporation, Limited had changed its name to the Newfoundland Power and Paper Company. Limited. The 1923 Act takes account of the company's expansion of its operations to include the generation and/or supply of &ldquo;hydraulic and/or electric or other power electric light and heat&rdquo; along with other industries. The 1923 Act amends various sections of the 1915 Act, and sets out the terms of the financial arrangement between the parties. It attaches, and approves and confirms, two agreements, constituting Part I and Part II of the Schedule to the 1923 Act. These agreements are themselves to further amend the 1915 Agreement and the 1915 Act.
<P1>Section 2, 1923 Act [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 11].</P1>
<P1>Section 14, 1923 Act [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 11].</P1></P>
<P>69. Part I of the Schedule to the 1923 Act is an agreement between three parties: Newfoundland Power and Paper Company Limited, Sir W.G. Armstrong Whitworth &amp; Company, Limited (an English company), and the Government of Newfoundland. Part II of the Schedule to the 1923 Act is an agreement between the Government of Newfoundland and Newfoundland Power and Paper Company, Limited. Its recitals provide:
<QUOTE><P>WHEREAS, the Government granted and conveyed to The Reid Newfoundland Company certain lands mentioned in the Schedule hereto and subsequently such lands and the timber rights thereon, in addition to all rights to water power, were conveyed and demised to the Company</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>70. Clause 2 of Part II of the Schedule to the 1923 Act confirms the conveyance and demise of these lands and rights to Newfoundland Power and Paper Company, Limited. The Schedule to Part II identifies the lands in question, as well as the following:
<QUOTE><P>All the water powers in and upon the Humber River, and in and upon Junction Brook, a portion of which water powers passed to The Reid Newfoundland Company by virtue of the said grants, and which portion has since been conveyed to the Company, and the remainder of which water powers was demised to the Company by the Agreement of 1915.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Clause 2 of the Schedule to Part II of the 1923 Agreement, pp. 34 [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 11].</P1></P>
<P>71. The above overview of the three acts in question and their associated agreements demonstrates that the general goal to which they were directed was to give effect to. and amend, agreements governing the regulatory and financial relationships between the Government of Newfoundland and the International Paper Company of Newfoundland, Limited (or predecessor companies), which conducted various operations at the given times.</P>
<P>72. Turning to the clause on which the Learned Judge bases the Decision&mdash;clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement&mdash;it is clear that it does not impose any mandatory arbitration on third parties. It does not <UNDER>create</UNDER> any arbitration obligations. Rather, it modifies the arbitration <UNDER>procedure</UNDER> originally set out in clause 8 of the 1923 legislation. Clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement is as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Clause 8 of the Agreement of 1923 shall not apply to the Company; but the following provision shall apply to the Company:
<QUOTE><P>Any questions, disputes or differences between the parties hereto, or between the Company and third parties <BOLD><UNDER>where provision for arbitration is made herein, or in the Act or Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements,</UNDER></BOLD> arising out of, under or in connection with this Agreement or the Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements, or the execution thereof, shall on the application of either party be submitted to the arbitration of three arbitrators and the provisions of Part VI. of the Judicature Act, Chapter 83 of the Consolidated Statutes (Third Series), except Section 212 and except as modified in this Clause, shall apply to any such submission. (...) [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>73. The purported arbitration clause does not itself create or expand any arbitration requirement for third parties. The words of the Act are to be read in their entire context and in their grammatical and ordinary sense: it provides direction as to the arbitration process to be followed <UNDER>when arbitration is triggered by a separate clause</UNDER>, whether under the 1927 Agreement, the 1915 Act or Agreement or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements (i.e. the 1923 Act or Agreement). That is the only reasonable interpretation of the clause. It does not compel arbitration.</P>
<P>74. The Respondent bore the burden, in the application below, of establishing that there was arbitration <UNDER>compelled</UNDER> by the legislation.</P>
<P>75. As the Learned Judge correctly concluded, there was no such provision in the 1915 and 1923 legislation and agreement. However, the Learned Judge concluded that clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement &ldquo;effectively&rdquo; compels arbitration:
<QUOTE><P>While Clause 2(n) does not explicitly refer to Section 14 of the 1915 Act, the matters set out in that clause effectively take away the right to litigate a claim in Court in favour of mandatory arbitration.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Decision, para. 42 [Appeal Book, Tab 3, Page 20].</P1></P>
<P>76. Absent <UNDER>express</UNDER> language to the contrary, in legislation or in a binding agreement, the Appellants have the right to initiate an action in Court. The Learned Judge's reasoning&mdash;that there is not a right to initiate and maintain an action in Court except if legislation <EM>grants</EM> such a right&mdash;sets the stage for a subsequent interpretation of the legislation that is incorrect.</P>
<P>77. The conclusion that the common law right to start an action has &ldquo;effectively&rdquo; been taken away is unsupported by the legislation, and is not the correct test in assessing whether the right to litigate has been removed by legislation.</P>
<P>78. The Learned Judge failed to reconcile his conclusion&mdash;that arbitration was compelled&mdash;with the wording of the statute.</P>
<P>79. To contend with the following language of clause 2(n), which is clearly problematic for the Learned Judge's conclusion&mdash;&ldquo;(...) where provision for arbitration is made herein, or in the Act or Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements,&rdquo;&mdash;he makes the following comment purporting to reconcile his conclusion with this language:
<QUOTE><P>The various clauses and provisions relating to claims and in particular Clause 15 of the 1915 Agreement contain an optional provision for arbitration which can be chosen by the claimants. The fact that a claimant could opt to initiate a claim in Court does not mean that there was no provision for arbitration.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Decision, paras. 44. 45 [Appeal Book, Tab 3. Page 21].</P1></P>
<P>80. Clause 15 of the 1915 Agreement provides as follows:
<QUOTE><P>If the Company, in or by reason of the exercise of any of the rights hereby granted, submerge, destroy, damage or injuriously affect any private rights, interests, lands or properly, and shall be unable to agree with the owner thereof as to compensation to be paid therefor, the Company, with the consent of the Governor in Council, may proceed with the exercise of the said rights, by these presents granted to the said Company, and the compensation to be paid by the Company to the owner, for or in respect to such rights, interests, lands or property, shall be settled by arbitration in the manner hereinbefore provided.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>81. However, section 14 of the 1915 Act provides as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Nothing herein or in the Schedule hereto in relation to the settlement of claims by arbitration shall be held or construed to prejudice or exclude the right of any claimant to institute an action in a Court of competent jurisdiction in respect to any such claim.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>82. The express reservation of the right to institute a court action by section 14 of the 1915 Act is clear and unambiguous. Section 14 expressly reserves the right of a claimant to commence a court action. Section 14 of the 1915 Act is not extinguished by any of the subsequent amending agreements. The Respondent had tried to argue that because Section 14 was &ldquo;not repeated in any other act&rdquo;, this somehow meant it was no longer in force. That is, of course, contrary to the rules of statutory interpretation. It is a basic principle of statutory interpretation that a subsequent general enactment is presumed not to interfere with a prior specific enactment, absent an intention clearly manifested to the contrary.
<P1>Transcript, pg. 20, lines 19-20 [Appeal Book, Tab 7, Page 58].</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Barker v. Edger</SOC><CITE>[1898] A.C. 748</CITE><COURTJUR>P.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, cited in <CASEREF><SOC>St. John's (City) v. FW Woolworth Co</SOC><CITE>[1980] N.J. No. 109</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>31 Nfld. &amp; P.E.I.R. 451</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> at para. 16 (overturned for different reasons, [1981] N.J. No. 61, 38 Nfld. &amp; P.E.I.R. 202) [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 9]; <CASEREF><SOC>Lovell v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>[1974] S.C.R. 1349</CITE></CASEREF> [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 3].</P1></P>
<P>83. The Learned Judge accepted the Appellants' position on this point that arbitration under clause 15 of the 1915 Agreement was optional, and he correctly concluded at paragraph 26 that &ldquo;a claimant had the right to pursue a claim in Court and was not restricted to arbitration by virtue of Section 14 of the 1915 Act.&rdquo; In other words, arbitration of what the Learned Judge refers to as nuisance carried out under statutory authority is <EM>optional</EM>.</P>
<P>84. However, the Learned Judge subsequently retreats from this interpretation, and carries on to commit two errors.</P>
<P>85. First, there is no evidence in the present case that the circumstances contemplated by clause 15 apply here; the Respondent has not conceded that an alleged nuisance has been caused by its activities, that the alleged damage is an inevitable result of legislatively authorized undertaking, or that it is liable to the Appellants.</P>
<P>86. Second, and more fundamentally, the Learned Judge relies on optional arbitration in clause 15 of the 1915 Agreement as satisfying the language of &ldquo;provision for arbitration&rdquo; in clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement. Although clause 15 of the 1915 Act is indeed &ldquo;provision for arbitration&rdquo;, he commits a fundamental error by, contrary to the legislation, converting what was <EM>optional</EM> arbitration&mdash;for claims of compensation for public nuisance where liability (including causation) is admitted (not the case here)&mdash;to the status of <EM>mandatory</EM> arbitration. With no support in the language of clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement, the Learned Judge interprets clause 2(n) to modify the status of <EM>optional</EM> arbitration to <EM>mandatory</EM> arbitration of the Appellants' claims. This is a reversible error. Clause 2(n) does <UNDER>not</UNDER> say that where arbitration was once optional, it is now mandatory. The Learned Judge errs by interpreting the legislation contrary to its true meaning, and plain wording, and to any possible contextual reading of the legislation, and in so doing imposes mandatory arbitration where there is no such legislative basis.</P>
<P>87. Unless the legislation clearly demands it, arbitration must not be imposed on the Appellants. The approach described in <EM>Archean</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> is directed to &ldquo;giving effect, as fully and faithfully as possible, to the meaning associated with the legislative act and counters the potential for substitution of judicial for legislative will.&rdquo; The Learned Judge commits a reversible error by departing from the approach prescribed by <EM>Archean</EM>.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Lynch v. St. John's (City</SOC><CITE>2016 NLCA 35</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>380 Nfld. &amp; P.E.I.R. 13</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> at para. 77 [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 4].</P1></P>
<P>88. The Learned Judge had said that &ldquo;The various clauses and provisions relating to claims and in particular Clause 15 of the 1915 Agreement contain an optional provision for arbitration which can be chosen by the claimants.&rdquo; He had analyzed each provision in the 1915 and 1923 legislation and had concluded that there was no imposition by such provision of mandatory arbitration of the Appellants' claims therein. He cannot convert optional arbitration (of matters irrelevant to this claim, in any event) to mandatory arbitration with no legislative basis to do so.</P>
<P>89. The Learned Judge has erred by overlooking the requirement to identify <EM>explicit</EM> language overriding the common law right to initiate civil action. He applies no such rigorous requirement to his interpretation. He does not explain how his decision to grant the stay is consistent with giving reasonable meaning to the language of clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement. Further, the Learned Judge contradicts himself in concluding on the one hand:
<QUOTE><P>[...] Clause 2(n) makes <UNDER>no reference</UNDER> to mandatory arbitration.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Decision, para. 44 [Appeal Book, Tab 3. Page 21].</P1></P>
<P>And on the other:
<QUOTE><P>Section 14 gave the option of arbitration or Court to a claimant, while Clause 2(n) <UNDER>mandated</UNDER> that both parties had to resort to arbitration.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Decision, para. 46 [Appeal Book, Tab 3, Page 21].</P1></P>
<P>90. The Learned Judge has made a leap to the second conclusion, contradicting his preceding assessment two paragraphs earlier that clause 2(n) makes no reference to mandatory arbitration, and with no support in the legislation. Again, clause 2(n) simply modifies the arbitration procedure to be followed <EM>when</EM> arbitration occurs. It is not in itself sufficient, or intended, to remove the right to initiate a claim in court.</P>
<P>91. The Learned Judge has implied terms that are not present in the legislation.</P>
<P>92. There is no manifest intention for clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement to have the effect of compelling arbitration of claims under Clause 15 of the 1915 Agreement (which, again, is concerned with claims of a different nature than those in the present case).</P>
<P>93. The Respondent filed no supporting evidence of a legislative intention to mandate arbitration. Counsel's submissions included speculation that the Respondent may have been &ldquo;reluctant to allow themselves to be the subject of access to the court&rdquo;, but there was no evidence that the legislature at the time intended to preclude access to the court. Nor was there any evidence to support the Respondent's suggestion that the legislature would have intended to make &ldquo;concessions&rdquo; of this nature (i.e. excluding the right of claimants to access the court) to encourage development by the Respondent. The following submissions made by the Respondents' counsel at the hearing were unsupported by any evidence:
<QUOTE><P>The companies themselves would be reluctant to allow themselves to be the subject of access to the courts that would delay and affect the development of the agreements and the development of the assets and so on and operations pursuant to the agreement, but they recognized that if we have injuriously affected anyone, that their rights are subject to arbitration provisions, which can be done in a summary way and done quickly, not through the laborious, and largely at that time, inaccessible access to the court.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Transcript, pp. 23-24, lines 20&ndash;25; 1&ndash;7 [Appeal Book, Tab 7, Page 58].</P1>
<QUOTE><P>When you read the Act, as a whole, you'll see the various concessions that are made by the government of the day to encourage and to permit this development. This development at the time, if you go through the documents to see the amounts of money involved&mdash;today, you know, 15 million dollars, may not in today's dollars seem like a lot. but back in 1915 and '23 and '27, these were huge, huge amounts of money and a huge commitment of resources on the part of the government, and a huge commitment of funds and liability on the part of the developers. It was not unusual that in coming to that kind of an arrangement that concessions and specific considerations in dealing with matters to facilitate that development are made by the government in favour of the party to whom they have entrusted the development of these resources. One of those is that disputes between what the company is authorized to do in this development and in the operation of the asset that it develops, is that if in doing any of these works it injuriously affects somebody else or causes damage to their property, the rights of that person are not interfered with, they are given the right to assert a claim, but those claims are dealt with in the arbitration process, not in the litigation process, and that was something that was obviously negotiated between the company and the government and the government agreed that this was a reasonable and fair way to go [...]</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Transcript, pp. 25-26, lines 12&ndash;25, 1&ndash;21 [Appeal Book, Tab 7, Page 59].</P1></P>
<P>94. Conjecture and speculation by counsel for the Respondent is not equivalent to evidence of legislative intention.</P>
<P>95. The legislation clearly does not mandate arbitration of the Appellants' claim, nor does it admit of ambiguity. However if there <EM>had been</EM> any ambiguity in the legislation suggesting that arbitration of the Appellants' claims <EM>may</EM> be compelled by clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement, such ambiguity should be resolved in favour of the Appellants' rights of access to the court.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Seidel v. TELUS Communications Inc.</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 15</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2011] 1 S.C.R. 531</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> at para. 47 [Appellants' Authorities, Tab 8].</P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>ISSUE TWO</TI>
<P><P1><EM>Did the Learned Judge commit a reversible error by declining to exercise discretion to dismiss the Jurisdiction Application?</EM></P1></P>
<P>96. Having concluded at paragraph 48 of the Decision that &ldquo;there has been finding for mandatory arbitration&rdquo;, the Learned Judge considered whether he ought nevertheless to exercise discretion to deny the requested stay. The Learned Judge reviews jurisprudence of the Supreme Court of Canada which, he concludes, &ldquo;has consistently held in a number of recent decisions that the presence of a mandatory arbitration clause precludes the Courts from having jurisdiction to determine the matter.&rdquo;
<P1>Decision, para. 52 [Appeal Book, Tab 3, Page 22].</P1></P>
<P>97. The Learned Judge's assessment of the discretion question contains a premise that the present matter is on equal footing with the cases he reviews. In those cases, however, the legislation or contract, as the case may be, mandated arbitration in the circumstances at hand. The scope of the legislation or contract was clear, requiring arbitration. Those cases were decided against a fundamentally different background.</P>
<P>98. This present matter is not one in which a statute specifically requires that the dispute in issue be referred to an arbitration process. Therefore there is no proper foundation from which to weigh, in a discretionary process, the characteristics of arbitration against the procedural vehicle of a class action.</P>
<P>99. Further, the established principles at play in the authorities relied upon by the Learned Judge are irrelevant; they are directed to upholding autonomy of the parties in question, respecting freedom of contract and clear legislative intent. For example the Learned Judge cites, at some length, <CASEREF><SOC>Seidel v. Telus Communications Inc</SOC></CASEREF>. The case is set against a a key principle; if parties freely enter into agreements by which they have agreed to arbitrate the matter in dispute, the parties will be referred to arbitration. The principle of liberal interpretation of arbitration clauses adopted by the parties rests upon the foundation of the mutual intention and agreement of the parties. The principles of freedom of contract and personal autonomy do not come into play in the present circumstances, where there is <UNDER>no contract</UNDER> between the Appellants and the Respondent, no mutual agreement relating to the procedure to be followed to resolve disputes, and thus no deference of autonomy to uphold.</P>
<P>100. The Learned Judge's reasons contain no indication that His Lordship reconciled the distinction between the present matter and the several cases he cites at pages 15 to 18 of the Decision, all of which are distinguishable on the basis that they involve bargaining between parties, a meeting of the minds by parties and upholding commercial certainty. For example, the context is consumer contracts in <EM>Dell, Rogers, Seidel</EM>, and labour relations governed by collective agreements in <EM>Weber</EM> and <EM>Basillion</EM>.</P>
<P>101. As submitted at the hearing, the primary argument being submitted by the Appellants is not that arbitration is <EM>less preferable</EM> to a class action; rather, arbitration is not legislated, and is therefore not compelled. There should be no engagement in a weighing of relative preferabilities by the Learned Judge.
<P1>Transcript, p. 57 lines 3&ndash;7 [Appeal Book, Tab 7, Page 61].</P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V"><UNDER>PART V: RELIEF SOUGHT</UNDER></TI>
<P>102. The Learned Judge committed reversible errors by granting the stay requested by the Respondent.</P>
<P>103. For the foregoing reasons, the Appellants respectfully request that the Decision be reversed and the Jurisdiction Application be dismissed.</P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED.</BOLD></P>
