<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. This is the Factum of the First_Respondent; Corner Brook Pulp and Paper Limited <BOLD>(&ldquo;the Company&rdquo;),</BOLD> in response to the appeal brought by the Appellants.</P>
<P>2. As a putative class proceeding, leave was required from the Case Management Judge, the Honourable Justice David F. Hurley, for the Company to bring the Interlocutory Application which is the subject of this Appeal.</P>
<P>3. Pursuant to Justice Hurley's June 17, 2016 Case Management Order, the Company brought Application pursuant to the <EM>Judicature Act</EM> (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Stay Application&rdquo;</BOLD>) to stay the proceeding and enforce arbitration obligations per the <EM>International Paper Co., Ltd. Act</EM>, Cap.4, 18 Geo. v. (1927) (the <BOLD>&ldquo;1927 Act&rdquo;</BOLD>) and related legislation and agreements with the force and effect of legislation (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Legislation&rdquo;</BOLD>).
<P1><BOLD>Case Management Order [Appeal Book, Tab 5]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Stay Application [Appeal Book, Tab 6]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>4. The Stay Application was framed on the express basis that the Company's rights and interests in the water control system continue pursuant to the Legislation. The Statement of Claim by which the action is brought asserts operations for &ldquo;nearly a century&rdquo; and identifies the Company amongst the &ldquo;Kruger Defendants&rdquo; which are described with reference to corporate successions tracing back to the International Power and Paper Company of Newfoundland Limited. The Stay Application was grounded on the affidavit of Darren Scott Pelley, Vice President and General Manager of the Company; it was not challenged by cross-examination and was accepted by Justice Hurley. It is disingenuous for the Appellant to now complain that relevant facts were unestablished.
<P1><BOLD>Stay Application [Appeal Book, Tab 6, para.4]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Statement of Claim [Appeal Book, Tab 4, paras. 1 and 12&ndash;16]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Pelley Affidavit [Appeal Book, Tab 7, paras. 3 and 5]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment [Appeal Book, Tab 3, para. 4]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Appellants' Factum, para. 62]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>5. The hearing of the Stay Application proceeded before Justice Hurley on December 7, 2016 with submissions by counsel for the Company, counsel for the Appellants, counsel for the Fourth Respondent (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Town&rdquo;)</BOLD> and counsel for the Fifth Respondent (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Province&rdquo;)</BOLD> on the application of the Legislation to the claims advanced in the Statement of Claim.</P>
<P>6. The Legislation amends and adopts agreements to &ldquo;promote the development of all enterprise in the Colony which will utilize its products and resources and create new industries&rdquo; between the Company and the Province, giving them the force and effect of law. Per the <EM>Interpretation Act</EM>, such preamble is intended to assist in explaining the purpose and object of the Legislation.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Newfoundland Products Corporation Act</EM>, Cap.4, 6 Geo.V. (1915) (the &ldquo;1915 Act&rdquo;) [Company's Authorities, Tab 11, s.1 and preamble to Schedule]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>1927 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 7, s.1 and cl.2 to Schedule]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Interpretation Act</EM>, RSNL 1990, c I-19 (the &ldquo;<EM>Interpretation Act</EM>&rdquo;) [Company's Authorities, Tab 8, s.14]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>7. Interpreted in context, as agreements evolved and were amended by statute and subsequent agreements in 1915, 1923 and 1927, the Legislation clearly dictates that disputes, including any alleged injurious impact upon private rights and interests, being the cause of action asserted by the Appellants in the within proceeding, be resolved by arbitration (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Arbitration Submission&rdquo;).</BOLD>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Interpretation Act</EM> [Company's Authorities, Tab 8, s.16]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>1927 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 7, cl.2 and cl.2.(n) of Schedule]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>8. Suggestions that Justice Hurley began from an erroneous premise are unfounded: the conclusion that, in 1915, the applicable legislation &ldquo;gave&rdquo; or &ldquo;created&rdquo; a right to litigate is taken out of context of the analysis which preceded it as to the impact of a term of agreement which compelled arbitration and its legislative approval and confirmation, subject to specific conditions including the declaration that the discretion to either litigate or arbitrate is not prejudiced or excluded. Justice Hurley's reference in considering the scope of the 1927 Act clearly relates to the conclusion that, in 1915, the legislation returned the right which the agreement approved and confirmed by that same legislation had taken away.
<P1><BOLD>[Appellants' Factum, para. 29 <EM>et seq.</EM>]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment [Appeal Book, Tab 3, paras. 13, 17, 19&ndash;26 and 41]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>1915 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 11, s.14 and cl.15 to Schedule]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>9. Since 1927 there has been no discretion as to whether disputes between the Company and Third Parties resulting from the exercise of rights granted by the Legislation should be arbitrated or litigated. The 1927 Act expressly obliges arbitration of disputes &ldquo;... where provision for arbitration is made ... in the Act or Agreement of 1915 ...&rdquo; and it is clear that provision for arbitration was made in the Agreement of 1915 for disputes such as the cause of action asserted by the Appellants in these proceedings.
<P1><BOLD>1927 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 7, cl.2.(n) to Schedule]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>1915 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 11, cl.15 to Schedule]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>10. Justice Hurley's decision on the Stay Application recognizes and extends deference to the Arbitration Submission in the Legislation after careful analysis, in context, of the interplay between the agreements and statutes enacted in 1915, 1923 and 1927 and thoughtful review of the applicable jurisprudence. Justice Hurley concludes that arbitration jurisdiction should be accepted and affirmed whether provided by legislation or when agreed to by the parties. He further recognizes that arbitration is regarded as an efficient means of dispute resolution, particularly as regards the development of resources for the public good.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment [Appeal Book, Tab 3, paras. 42&ndash;47, 57 and 60]</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II"><UNDER>PART II&mdash;CONCISE STATEMENT OF FACTS</UNDER></TI>
<P>11. Over the past century, the Legislation has, from time to time, been amended to reflect the renegotiation of the agreements between the Company and the Province, pursuant to which the Company and its corporate predecessors have operated. For example, Clauses 2 and 11 of the Schedule to the 1927 Act clarify how obligations are modified and how successors to the original signatory to the agreement are also bound:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>2. The Company shall be entitled to all the rights, powers, privileges, franchises and exemptions vested in, or owned or enjoyed by the Old Company under the Act and Agreement of 1915 and the Subsequent Acts and Agreements, and shall be bound by all the obligations Imposed upon the Old Company under said Acts and Agreements, except in so far as such rig hts, powers, privileges, franchises and exemptions and such obligations are extended, modified or otherwise affected by the following ...</BOLD></P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P><BOLD>11. In this Agreement wherever the context admits the expression &ldquo;the Company&rdquo; shall be held to include the International Paper Company of Newfoundland, Limited, and the assigns of all or substantially all its property and assets;</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>1927 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 7, cl.2 and cl.11 of Schedule]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>12. Contrary to assertions by the Appellants, Justice Hurley did extend a modern approach to interpretation of the Legislation: analysis of the 1927 Act is predicated on understanding the agreements and legislation which preceded it and are referenced within it:
<P1>(a) The <EM>Newfoundland Products Corporation Act</EM>, (the <BOLD>&ldquo;1915 Act&rdquo;)</BOLD> includes and confirms an agreement entered April 16, 1915 between the corporate predecessor to the Company and the Province; and</P1>
<P1>(b) The <EM>Nfld. Power and Paper Co., Ltd. Act</EM>, (the <BOLD>&ldquo;1923 Act&rdquo;)</BOLD> includes and confirms an agreement entered June 9, 1923 between the corporate predecessor to the Company and the Province.</P1>
<P1>The 1915 and 1923 legislation is interpreted as it was amended in 1927 and effective to date; it is not considered in isolation.
<P2><BOLD>1915 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 11, s.1]</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD><EM>Nfld. Power and Paper Co., Ltd. Act</EM>, Cap.1, 14 Geo.V. (1923) (the &ldquo;1923 Act&rdquo;) [Company's Authorities, Tab 12, s.14]</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>1927 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 7]</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>13. The Company's rights and obligations in reference to the water control system, being how the allegations are introduced in the Statement of Claim, are governed by the 1915 Act, the 1923 Act and the 1927 Act, as each has been amended. The 1915 Act and the 1927 Act make provision for a process of arbitration for the resolution of disputes with third parties; the 1923 Act amends and confirms the 1915 Act.
<P1><BOLD>1915 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 11, cl.15 of Schedule]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>1923 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 12, s.14]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>1927 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 7, s.1 and cl.2(n) of Schedule]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>14. As contrasted to contracts which normally bind only parties thereto, the agreements legislated within the 1915 Act, the 1923 Act and the 1927 Act have been given the force and effect of law, which is of particular significance insofar as they address third party interests. Unless declared to be a private Act by express provision, every Act is considered to be a public Act. To the extent that it may be suggested that there is any doubt as to meaning, public Act are construed it keeping in view that they are taken to have been passed for the public advantage.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Interpretation Act</EM> [Company's Authorities, Tab 8, s.5]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ottawa v. Royal Trust Co.</SOC><CITE>[1964] SCR 526</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>1964 CanLII 13</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Company's Authorities, Tab 3, p.540]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>15. The preference or legislative intent to compel arbitration is clear based on the express wording of the Legislation, both with reference to disputes relating to third party interests, as asserted by the Appellants, and as between parties to agreements incorporated therein. Justice Hurley recognized the various examples of this legislative intent throughout his Reasons for Judgment.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment [Appeal Book, Tab 3, paras. 11&ndash;18, 34, 40 and 42&ndash;47]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>16. The currently operative Arbitration Submission resides in the 1927 Act and is as follows:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>2. The Company shall be entitled to all the rights, powers, privileges, franchises and exemptions vested in, or owned or enjoyed by the Old Company under the Act and Agreement of 1915 and the Subsequent Acts and Agreements, and shall be bound by all the obligations Imposed upon the Old Company under said Acts and Agreements, except in so far as such rights, powers, privileges, franchises and exemptions and such obligations are extended, modified or otherwise affected by the following provisions:</BOLD></P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P><BOLD>(n) Clause 8 of the Agreement of 1923 shall not apply to the Company; but the following provision shall apply to the Company:</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>Any questions, disputes or differences between the parties hereto, or between the Comp any and third parties where provision for arbitration is made herein, or in the Act or Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements, arising out of, under or in connection with this Agreement or the Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements, or the execution thereof, shall on the application of either party be submitted to the arbitration of three arbitrators and the provisions of Part VI. of the Judicature Act, Chapter 83 of the Consolidated Statutes (Third Series), except Section 212 and except as modified in this Clause, shall apply to any such submission. One arbitrator shall be appointed by each of the parties and the third by the two so appointed. If either party does not appoint an arbitrator within twenty days after request in writing from the other party, or if the two arbitrators do not appoint the third within twenty days of the appointment of the second of such two, the Supreme Court or a Judge thereof may upon application by either party appoint such arbitrator or arbitrators. The award of the arbitrators or any two of them shall be final and binding upon the parties thereto, unless appeal therefrom shall be made to the Supreme Court and notice of such appeal shall be filed in the Registry of the Supreme Court within thirty days from the date of such award.</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>1927 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 7, cl. 2.(n) of Schedule]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>17. The 1923 Act amended the 1915 Act and the agreement therein, including as stated in section 14:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>14.</N><SECP>THE Agreement of 1915 and the Act of 1915, are hereby further amended by the terms and conditions contained in the Agreements forming Part I and Part II of the Schedule to this Act, which Agreements are hereby approved and confirmed.</SECP></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>1923 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 12, s.14]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>18. Declared in the 1927 Act to no longer apply to the Company, clause 8 of the agreement of 1923 had prescribed mandatory arbitration as follows:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>8. ANY questions, disputes or differences arising out of, under or in connection with this Agreement or the execution thereof shall, on the application of either party, be referred to the award and final determination of two disinterested persons, one to be appointed by each of the parties in difference, and if the arbitrators failed to agree, then to the award, umpirage and final determination of an umpire to be appointed by the arbitrators, and the award of such arbitrators or umpire shall be final and binding on both parties, and any such reference shall be deemed a submission to arbitration within the meaning of the Judicature Act, Chapter 83 of the Consolidated Statutes of Newfoundland (third series).</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>1923 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 12, cl. 8. of Schedule Part II]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>19. The provision for arbitration in the agreement within the 1915 Act, as referenced in clause 2 .(n) of the agreement within the 1927 Act, states as follows:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>15. If the Company, in or by reason of the exercise of any of the rights hereby granted, submerge, destroy, damage or injuriously affect any private rights, interest, lands or property, and shall be unable to agree with the owner thereof as to compensation to be paid therefor, the Company, with the consent of the Governor in Council, may proceed with the exercise of the said rights, by these presents granted to the said Company, and the compensation to be paid by the Company to the owner, for or in respect to such rights, interest, lands or property, shall be settled by arbitration in the manner hereinbefore provided.</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>1915 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 11, cl. 15. of Schedule]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>20. The 1927 Act expressly confirms that successors to the original party to the agreement contained therein are also bound:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>11. In this Agreement wherever the context admits the expression &ldquo;the Company&rdquo; shall be held to include the International Paper Company of Newfoundland, Limited, and the assigns of all or substantially all its property and assets;</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>1927 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 7, cl.2 and cl.11 of Schedule]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>21. The mandatory Arbitration Submission and the intention to amend the Legislation, as it existed to that point, is reinforced by clause 5 of the Schedule to the 1927 Legislation:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>5. The Company may, as incidental to the exercise of its rights under Clause 1 of the Agreement of 1915, as affected by the Act of 1915, and under any other grants or demise of water powers which the Company shall acquire, regulate the amount of water flowing in the streams, lakes and watercourses referred to in said Clause 1 or in said other grants or demises in such manner as it may require for its operations; provided that the Company shall pay for such damage as it may cause thereby in accordance with the provisions in that respect of the Act and Agreement of 1915 as affected by the Subsequent Acts and Agreements.</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>1927 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 7, cl. 5 of Schedule]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>22. Since 1927 there have been no amendments to the Legislation which alter the Arbitration Submission.</P>
<P>23. The Plaintiffs have not commenced the process for arbitration, even though arbitration is the exclusive remedy available pursuant to the Legislation.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III"><UNDER>Part 3&mdash;LIST OF ISSUES</UNDER></TI>
<P>24. The following are submitted as the issues relevant to the determination of this matter:
<P1>Issue 1. Was there a reviewable error in concluding that the 1927 Act obliges arbitration?</P1>
<P1>Issue 2. Did Justice Hurley err in declining to exercise discretion to deny the Stay Application?</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV"><UNDER>PART 4&mdash;ARGUMENT</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Issue"><N>1</N><TI>WAS THERE A REVIEWABLE ERROR IN CONCLUDING THAT THE 1927 ACT OBLIGES ARBITRATION?</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>(a)</N><TI>Did Justice Hurley assume that rights to litigate and not arbitrate disputes must be granted?</TI>
<P>25. Suggestions are unfounded that Justice Hurley began analysis of the Stay Application from the erroneous premise that the right to litigate disputes existed only by express grant. His conclusion that the applicable legislation in 1915 &ldquo;gave&rdquo; or &ldquo;created&rdquo; a right to litigate is taken out of context of earlier discussion of the impact of the legislation passed June 5, 1915 which &ldquo;... approved and confirmed, subject to ... conditions and exceptions...&rdquo; the agreement dated April 16, 1915 and incorporated in the 1915 Act.
<P1><BOLD>[Appellants' Factum, para. 29 <EM>et seq.</EM>]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment [Appeal Book, Tab 3, paras. 13, 17, 19&ndash;26 and 41]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>26. The Agreement dated April 16, 1915 between the Company and the Province expressly provided that claims made by third parties for damages alleged to result from the Company's exercise of rights granted under the Agreement: &ldquo;... shall be settled by arbitration in the manner hereinbefore provided.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>1915 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 11, cl. 15. of Schedule]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>27. The 1915 Act confirms the Agreement dated April 16, 1915 subject to conditions, including the proviso in section 14 that:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>14.</N><SECP>Nothing herein or in the Schedule hereto in relation to the settlement of claims by arbitration shall be held or construed to prejudice or exclude the right of any claim ant to institute in action in a Court of competent jurisdiction in respect to any such claim.</SECP></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>1915 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 11, s.1 and s.14]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>28. Having already discussed and concluded that in 1915 the Agreement would oblige arbitration but that, by operation of the 1915 Act, the Agreement was modified to reinstate the discretion to arbitrate or to litigate, Justice Hurley's statement that: &ldquo;... the 1915 legislation gave claimants this right [to litigate] ...&rdquo; should not be taken out of context to suggest an erroneous presumption that the right to litigate had to be &ldquo;given&rdquo; and did not otherwise exist in law. To the contrary, the statement clearly means that the right ousted by the Agreement was given back by the statute's modification of the Agreement.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment [Appeal Book, Tab 3, paras. 13, 17, 19&ndash;26 and 41]</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>(b)</N><TI>Does the language in clause 2.(n) accord with the decision to grant the Stay Application?</TI>
<P>29. The Legislation reflects the evolution of various agreements between the Company and the Province, incorporating while modifying and confirming such pre -existing agreements, including confirmation that the agreements have the force and effect of law. While shaped by its predecessors, the 1927 Act governs the issue at hand of the Arbitration Submission.</P>
<P>30. It is disingenuous to suggest that the Legislation might not be relevant to current claims given that the Appellants' claims against the Company are framed in the Statement of Claim in reference to the Company's ongoing operations &ldquo;for nearly a century&rdquo; and identify the Company amongst the &ldquo;Kruger Defendants&rdquo; which are described with reference to corporate successions tracing back to the International Power and Paper Company of Newfoundland Limited. The Stay Application was itself expressly framed on the basis that the Company's rights and interests in the water control system, as it is described in the Statement of Claim, were created by and continue pursuant to the Legislation. The Appellants did not challenge evidence led on behalf of the Company by cross-examination of its deponent, and the evidence was accepted by Justice Hurley.
<P1><BOLD>Statement of Claim [Appeal Book, Tab 4, paras. 1 and 12&ndash;16]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Stay Application [Appeal Book, Tab 6, para. 4]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Pelley Affidavit [Appeal Book, Tab 7, paras. 3 and 5]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment [Appeal Book, Tab 3, paras. 4 - 5 ]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>31. The 1927 Act expressly states that the agreement dated August 2, 1927, and incorporated therein as a schedule, has &ldquo;... the force and effect of law.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>1927 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 7, s.1]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>32. Since 1927, the legislatively-prescribed mechanism to pursue a cause of action such as is asserted by the Appellants is by arbitration:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>2. The Company shall be entitled to all the rights, powers, privileges, franchises and exemptions vested in, or owned or enjoyed by the Old Company under the Act and Agreement of 1915 and the Subsequent Acts and Agreements, and shall be bound by all the obligations Imposed upon the Old Company under said Acts and Agreements, except in so far as such rights, powers, privileges, franchises and exemptions and such obligations are extended, modified or otherwise affected by the following provisions:</BOLD></P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P><BOLD>(n) Clause 8 of the Agreement of 1923 shall not apply to the Company; but the following provision shall apply to the Company:</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>Any questions, disputes or differences between the parties hereto, or between the Company and third parties where provision for arbitration is made herein, or in the Act or Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements, arising out of, under or in connection with this Agreement or the Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements, or the execution thereof, shall on the application of either party be submitted to the arbitration of three arbitrators and the provisions of Part VI. of the Judicature Act, Chapter 83 of the Consolidated Statutes (Third Series), except Section 212 and except as modified in this Clause, shall apply to any such submission. One arbitrator shall be appointed by each of the parties and the third by the two so appointed. If either party does not appoint an arbitrator within twenty days after request in writing from the other party, or if the two arbitrators do not appoint the third within twenty days of the appointment of the second of such two, the Supreme Court or a Judge thereof may upon application by either party appoint such arbitrator or arbitrators. The award of the arbitrators or any two of them shall be final and binding upon the parties thereto, unless appeal therefrom shall be made to the Supreme Court and notice of such appeal shall be filed in the Registry of the Supreme Court within thirty days from the date of such award.</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>1927 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 7, cl. 2.(n) of Schedule]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>33. For convenience, the Arbitration Submission operates as follows:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>2.(n)... Any ... disputes ... between the Company and third parties where provision for arbitration is made ... in the Act or Agreement of 1915 ... shall ... be submitted to the arbitration of three arbitrators and the provisions of Part VI. of the Judicature Act, Chapter 83 of the Consolidated Statutes (Third Series), except Section 212 and except as modified in this Clause, shall apply to any such submission.</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>1927 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 7, cl. 2.(n) of Schedule]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>34. The Agreement of 1915 is defined in the recitals of the Schedule to the 1927 Act as:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>The Agreement dated the 16th day of April, 1915, between His Excellency, the Governor of Newfoundland in Council, of the one part, and the Newfoundland Products Corporation. Limited (the original name of the Old Company), of the other part, hereinafter referred to as &ldquo;the Agreement of 1915&rdquo;;</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>1927 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 7, recitals of Schedule]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>35. The Agreement of 1915 is incorporated as a schedule to the 1915 Act and includes the following provision for arbitration (as such term is used in clause 2.(n) of the Schedule to the 1927 Act):
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>15. If the Company, in or by reason of the exercise of any of the rights hereby granted, submerge, destroy, damage or injuriously affect any private rights, interests, lands or property, and shall be unable to agree with the owner thereof as to compensation to be paid therefor, the Company, with the consent of the Governor in Council, may proceed with the exercise of the said rights, by these presents granted to the said Company, and the compensation to be paid by the Company to the owner, for or in respect to such rights, interest, lands or property, shall be settled by arbitration in the manner hereinbefore provided.</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>1915 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 11, cl.15 of Schedule]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>36. While the Agreement of 1915 was modified by section 14 of the 1915 Act to reinstate the discretion to litigate where the agreement had made arbitration mandatory, clause 2.(n) of the Schedule to the 1927 Act expressly references the &ldquo;...the Act <BOLD><UNDER>or</UNDER></BOLD> Agreement of 1915 ...&rdquo; and, the Agreement of 1915 having been expressly defined without reference to modification by the Act, there is no basis to suggest that discretion to litigate should modify the Arbitration Submission.
<P1><BOLD>1915 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 11, s.14]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>1927 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 7, recitals and cl.2 of Schedule]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>37. Justice Hurley's conclusions that clause 2.(n) of the Schedule to the 1927 Act compels arbitration as contemplated by clause 15 of the Agreement of 1915 and reinforced by clause 5 of the Schedule to 1927 Act are plainly sustained by principles of modern interpretation of statute. As set forth in the <EM>Interpretation Act</EM>:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>16.</N><SECP>Every Act and every regulation and every provision of an Act or regulation shall be considered remedial and shall receive the liberal construction and interpretation that best ensures the attainment of the objects of the Act, regulation, or provision according to its true meaning.</SECP></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Interpretation Act</EM> [Company's Authorities, Tab 8, s.16]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>38. The decision of this Honourable Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Archean Resources Ltd. v. Newfoundland (Minister of Finance)</SOC></CASEREF> is frequently cited for the direction provided by The Honourable Justice Green in interpreting legislation. For example, it is applied by this Honourable Court in the 2017 decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Penney v. Newfoundland and Labrador (Service NL)</SOC></CASEREF> with reference to the extrapolation of legislative intention through consideration of each provision of the statute as remedial and, with reference to academic authority, the consideration of the immediate and broader context in which the provision in question exists. In that matter, this Court considered statements in the House of Assembly in May of 2000 when the bill that eventually became the statute in question was introduced.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Penney v. Newfoundland and Labrador (Service NL)</SOC><CITE>2017 NLCA 25 (CanLII)</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Company's Authorities, Tab 4, paras. 17&ndash;21]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>39. In the matter at hand, the issue alleged is the interpretation of the Arbitration Submission, a clause in an agreement given the force and effect of law in a public Act. The context in which the Arbitration Clause was created can be determined through the recitals and specific clauses of such agreement, being the schedule to the 1927 Act.
<P1>(a) The Company operated under a series of agreements and statutes created between 1915 and 1925, enumerated and defined collectively as the &ldquo;Subsequent Acts and Agreements&rdquo;;
<P2><BOLD>1927 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 7, recitals of Schedule]</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>(b) The Agreement of 1915 in its first recital states its objective to be: &ldquo;... to promote the development of all enterprises in the Colony which utilize its products and resources and create new industries;&rdquo;
<P2><BOLD>1915 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 11, recitals of Schedule]</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>(c) Through 1915, 1923 and 1927, the agreements and statutes which govern the development of public resources to create industry consistently direct that disputes arising through the Company's operations be resolved by arbitration. Most are not relevant to specific claims of the Appellants but all illustrate the legislative intention to mandate dispute resolution and to bind third parties to the agreements:
<P2>i.) From the 1915 Act:
<P3>(1) Section 13 prescribes the procedure for arbitration;</P3>
<P3>(2) Section 14 reserves discretion to litigate notwithstanding provision to the contrary for resolution of claims by arbitration;</P3>
<P3>(3) Section 19 obliges that disputes in relation to the depreciation of preexisting third-party rights to develop water power be determined by arbitration;</P3>
<P3>(4) Clause 2 obliges arbitration when agreement cannot be reached on the amount payable to the Company by third parties for the Company's works for power;</P3>
<P3>(5) Clause 3 obliges arbitration when agreement cannot be reached for the price for power supplied by the Company to third parties;</P3>
<P3>(6) Clause 10 obliges arbitration for settlement of payment to third-party land owners or occupiers for expropriation of their property;</P3>
<P3>(7) Clause 15 obliges arbitration of third party claims for damages alleged to result from the Company's operations pursuant to the 1915 Act; and</P3>
<P3>(8) Clause 16 obliges arbitration of claims by the Crown for damages al leged to result from the Company's operations pursuant to the 1915 Act;</P3></P2>
<P2>ii.) From the 1923 Act:
<P3>(1) Section 11 directs that the price payable to the Company for the possible sale of hydro-electric power for the Newfoundland Railroad is to be agreed upon, failing which it will be fixed by arbitration; and</P3>
<P3>(2) Clause 8 questions, disputes or differences between parties to the agreement shall be determined by arbitration;</P3></P2>
<P2>iii.) From the 1927 Act:
<P3>(1) Clause 2.(n) mandates arbitration where provision for arbitration is made in the 1927 Act &ldquo;... or in the Act or Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements ...&rdquo;;</P3>
<P3>(2) Clause 5 provides that any damages caused by exercise of its rights to maintain dams and reservoirs for the purpose of its works and operations shall be paid by the Company in accordance with the Act and Agreement of 1915 as affected by the Subsequent Acts and Agreements; and</P3>
<P3>(3) Clause 9.(d) obliges arbitration when no agreement is reached to set compensation where claims that rights of third-party riparian owners are impacted by the Company's exercise of rights to dam and regulate the flow of water.
<P4><BOLD>1915 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 11, ss.13, 14 and 19 and recitals, cl.2, 3, 10, 15 and 16 of Schedule]</BOLD></P4>
<P4><BOLD>1923 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 12, s.11 and cl.8 of Schedule]</BOLD></P4>
<P4><BOLD>1927 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 7, cl.2, 5 and 9 of Schedule]</BOLD></P4></P3></P2></P1></P>
<P>40. The intention of the Legislature to mandate arbitration and bind third parties is clear on the face of the statutes and the agreements which they modify and confirm. Clause 2. (n) of the schedule to the 1927 Act confirms that arbitration is obliged where it is provided in the Act or the Agreement of 1915 and nothing amends that obligation since 1927. There is no ambiguity in the clear wording and remedial interpretation or in the continuity with the objective of promoting business and enterprise by allowing development to proceed while preserving a commercially efficient mechanism of dispute resolution for disputes or claims which may result.</P>
<P>41. Since 1927 there have been no amendments to the Legislation which alter the Arbitration Submission. The compulsory arbitration legislated in 1927 continues in full force and effect today.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Issue"><N>2</N><TI>DID JUSTICE HURLEY ERR IN DECLINING TO EXERCISE DISCRETION TO DENY THE STAY APPLICATION?</TI>
<P>42. Contrary to assertions by the Appellant, having concluded that the Legislation directs arbitration for the resolution of disputes such as the cause of action asserted by the Appellants, Justice Hurley correctly considered the applicable common law and statutes to determine whether a stay was appropriate.</P>
<P>43. The <EM>Judicature Act</EM> provides as follows in section 97:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>97.</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>The court may direct a stay of proceedings pending before it.</SSECP></SSEC>
<SSEC><N>(2)</N><SSECP>A person, whether or not that person is a party to the proceeding
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>who would have been entitled, if The Newfoundland Judicature Act, 1889 had not been enacted, to apply to the court to restrain the prosecution of the proceeding; or</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>who may be entitled to enforce an order, contrary to which proceedings may have been taken,</PARAP></PARA>
may apply in a summary way for a stay of the proceedings either generally or where necessary for the purposes of justice, and the court shall make the order that may be just.</SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Judicature Act</EM>, RSNL 1990, c. J-4 [Company's Authorities, Tab 9, s.97]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>44. The common law has variously considered when a stay is appropriate and has generated a consistent body of jurisprudence illuminating the issue, which jurisprudence Justice Hurley has appropriately considered and applied in the Reasons for Decision. The Company adopts and confirms its submissions on the Stay Application in reference to point.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment [Appeal Book, Tab 3, paras. 51&ndash;54]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Memorandum of Fact and Law of the Company [Appeal Book, Tab 9, paras. 32&ndash;40]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>45. With specific reference to the generally accepted approach of extending deference to the legislature's express preference for arbitration:
<P1>(a) In the decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Alberici Western Constructors Ltd. v Saskatchewan Power Corp.</SOC></CASEREF> the Saskatchewan Court of Queen's Bench granted two applications to stay proceedings on the basis that the issues were governed by arbitration provisions. Citing a decision of the Manitoba Court of Appeal, the Court articulates &ldquo;the general attitude courts have adopted in the treatment of these [arbitration] clauses&rdquo;:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>59 While the foundational principles are clear, in recent years, courts of all levels have recognized the many benefits of consensual contractual arbitration and have adopted a broad-minded attitude to the applicability and interpretation of such clauses. This is consistent with, and in keeping with, the amendments to the arbitration legislation across Canada and internationally. Geoff R. Hall, in his text &ldquo;Canadian Contractual Interpretation Law, 2d ed. (Markham: LexisNexis Canada Inc., 2012), states (at pp. 227-28):</BOLD>
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>The courts have repeatedly held that arbitration clauses are to be given a large and liberal interpretation. The position in Quebec is the same as in common law Canada. This approach has an unabashed policy goal: it furthers the modern trend of comity being extended by the judiciary to private dispute resolution procedures which have been adopted by the parties. <UNDER><EM>It also reflects the policy embodied in the modern Arbitration Acts that directs the court's not to interfere in arbitrations</EM></UNDER>. Such an approach is different from that which prevailed in an earlier era, in which the courts jealously guarded their jurisdiction and tended to interpret arbitration provisions narrowly. Cases from that era are now not followed. [<UNDER>Emphasis added</UNDER>]</BOLD></P></QUOTE></P></QUOTE>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Alberici Western Constructors Ltd. v Saskatchewan Power Corp.</SOC><CITE>2015 SKQB 74</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2015] S.J. No. 134</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> <BOLD>(upheld on appeal, 2016 SKCA 46 (CanLII)) [Company's Authorities, Tab 1, para. 59]</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>(b) This Court in its decision on <CASEREF><SOC>Midnight Marine Ltd. v Oppenheim</SOC></CASEREF> has likewise recognized the preference to favour arbitration where it has been directed by the Legislature.
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>[58] At paras. 59&ndash;70, Clarke J. also reviewed the English cases. He noted, as one of four factors bearing on the interpretation of the arbitration clause in Ace Capital, the strong U.S. policy in favour of arbitration, embodied in the Federal Arbitration Act and confirmed by the U.S. Supreme Court in</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Moses H. Cone Memorial Hospital v. Mercury Construction Corp.</SOC><CITE>103 S.Ct. 927</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(U.S. 1983):</BOLD>
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>The Arbitration Act establishes that, as a matter of federal law, any doubts concerning the scope of arbitral issues should be resolved in favour of arbitration whether the problem at hand is the construction of the contract language itself or an allegation of waiver, delay, or the like defence to arbitrability.</BOLD></P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>The same policy in favour of arbitration is found in this Province's International Commercial Arbitration Act, RSNL 1990, c. 1&ndash;15. This statute incorporates the Convention on the Recognition and Enforcement of Foreign Arbitration Awards and the Model Law on International Arbitration, adopted by the United Nations Commission on International Trade Law, into the law of this Province.</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Midnight Marine Ltd. v Oppenheim</SOC><CITE>2010 NLCA 64</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Company's Authorities, Tab 2, Para. 58]</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>46. Arbitration is recognized to be an accessible, efficient and effective dispute resolution procedure, particularly in circumstances where interests of the general public are impacted by operation and policy of legislatively-sanctioned rights. For example, the Province directs arbitration in lieu of litigation in the following circumstances:
<P1>(a) Pursuant to the <EM>Petroleum and Natural Gas Act</EM>, where a permitee or a leasee to drilling rights for petroleum is alleged to have caused damage or injury to a third party property owner by exercise of rights under such permit or lease, the claims for such damage or injury must be determined by arbitration.</P1>
<P1>(b) The <EM>Petroleum Regulations</EM> under the <EM>Petroleum and Natural Gas Act</EM> further provide that, where an interest holder disputes a decision of the minister with respect to renewal or termination or suspension of obligations, as prescribed therein, that dispute shall be referred to arbitration.</P1>
<P1>(c) Under the <EM>Muskrat Falls Project Land Use and Expropriation Act</EM>, the proponent has authority to expropriate in order to proceed with the project and, if no direct agreement can be reached, the compensation of any land owner incidentally impacted shall be determined by arbitration.</P1>
<P1>(d) Pursuant to the <EM>City of St. John's Act</EM>, if an approved development should result in the alteration of streets, requiring the expropriation of adjoining land, the City can expropriate such land as it deems appropriate and the resulting loss to the landowner shall be determined by arbitration.
<P2><BOLD><EM>Petroleum and Natural Gas Act</EM>, RSNL1990 c P-10 [Company's Authorities, Tab 13, s. 21]</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD><EM>Petroleum Regulations under the Petroleum and Natural Gas Act</EM>, CNLR 1151/96 [Company's Authorities, Tab 14, s. 68]</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD><EM>Muskrat Falls Project Land Use and Expropriation Act</EM>, SNL 2012 [Company's Authorities, Tab 10, Part II]</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD><EM>City of St. John's Act</EM>, RSNL1990 c C-17 [Company's Authorities, Tab 6, s. 83]</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>47. Justice Hurley specifically accepted the ratio of the British Columbia Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Ruddell v BC Rail Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, where it was held that because the preference for arbitration was found in a statute enacted by the legislature such preference would displace the right to otherwise bring a class proceeding. The Court accordingly issued a stay of proceedings, noting the efficiency and flexibility of arbitration, as well as the potentially broad application of an arbitration decision, as factors mitigating in favour of arbitration.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment [Appeal Book, Tab 3, para. 51]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ruddell v BC Rail Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2007 BCCA 269</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD><EM>(leave to appeal to SCC dismissed: [2007] SCCA No 354)</EM> [Company's Authorities, Tab 5, paras. 31&ndash;42]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>48. In its first recital the Agreement of 1915 states its objective to be: &ldquo;... to promote the development of all enterprises in the Colony which utilize its products and resources and create new industries.&rdquo; There is no suggestion that the Province exceeded its jurisdiction in determining the terms and conditions for such enterprise, including setting the mechanism for resolution of any disputes resulting from the exploitation of public resources. Having exercised such jurisdiction it does not behoove this Court to second guess the decisions made and agreements reached by the Province.
<P1><BOLD>1915 Act [Company's Authorities, Tab 11, recitals of Schedule]</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V"><UNDER>Part 5&mdash;RELIEF SOUGHT</UNDER></TI>
<P>49. The Company respectfully requests:
<P1>(a) That the appeal be dismissed;</P1>
<P1>(b) That the Order of Justice Hurley dated December 15, 2017 be affirmed; and</P1>
<P1>(c) Such further relief as this Honourable Court may deem just.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD></P>
