<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. The Town supports the Appellants in the within appeal. It adopts the facts and argument as set out in the Appellants' Factum.</P>
<P>2. In addition to the arguments raised by the Appellants, the applications judge incorrectly concluded that the Arbitration Clause applied in the same manner to claims between the Government and the Company as compared to those between the Company and third parties, such as the Appellants. In doing so, the applications judge incorrectly applied the modern approach to statutory interpretation and committed an error in law.</P>
<P>3. The applications judge committed a reviewable error in failing to consider and exercise his discretionary power under the Arbitration Act to refrain from staying the proceedings against the Company. The applications judge's reasons failed to address or consider the Judicial Discretion Provision in the Arbitration Act and, in doing so, failed to distinguish the relied upon jurisprudence in light of the Judicial Discretion Provision that is unique to our Arbitration Act.</P>
<P>4. The Town respectfully submits that the applications judge committed reviewable errors in his findings of law. The Decision ought to be overturned, and the Jurisdiction Application denied.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;CONCISE STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P>5. The Fourth Respondent, the Town of Deer Lake (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Town&rdquo;</BOLD>), agrees with the Concise Statement of Facts as set out in the Appellants' Factum.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;LIST OF THE ISSUES</TI>
<P>6. The Appellants have provided a list of issues for consideration by this Court:</P>
<P>7. What is the appropriate standard of review in the within appeal?</P>
<P>8. Did the applications judge commit reviewable errors in failing to apply the proper principles of statutory interpretation, and in so doing concluding that clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Arbitration Clause&rdquo;</BOLD>) required the Appellants to refer their claims against the Company to arbitration?</P>
<P>9. Did the applications judge err in declining to exercise discretion to dismiss the Jurisdiction Application?</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>Standard of review</TI>
<P>10. The governing authority on the standard of review in a civil proceeding is <CASEREF><SOC>Housen v Nikolaisen</SOC></CASEREF>. The Town agrees with the Appellants in their identification of the applicable jurisprudence on this point.
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: Factum of the Appellants at &para;52, p 14.</P1>
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <CASEREF><SOC>Housen v Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 33</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2002] 2 SCR 235</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>11. The Town agrees with the Appellants that the standard applicable to Issue 1 is correctness. The Town further agrees that Issue 2 is an exercise in discretion and the applicable standard of review would be one of palpable and overriding error, unless the error amounted to an error at law, which would be subject to a standard of correctness.
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: Factum of the Appellants at &para;&para;53-54, p 14.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>The Legislation does not Prescribe Arbitration of the Appellants' Claims</TI>
<P>12. The applications judge was incorrect in his determination that the Arbitration Clause in the 1927 Act requires arbitration of the Appellants' claims, which warrants interference on appeal.</P>
<P>13. The 1927 Act does not mandate arbitration with respect to the Appellants' claims, and the Appellants have the residual remedy to litigate their dispute with the Company in the court of inherent jurisdiction, being the Supreme Court of Newfoundland and Labrador.</P>
<P>14. As stated by the Supreme Court of Canada in the seminal decision of <CASEREF><SOC>Re Rizzo &amp; Rizzo Shoes Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, the modern approach to statutory interpretation requires a reading of the words of an Act &ldquo;in their entire context, in their grammatical and ordinary sense harmoniously with the scheme of the act, the object of the Act, and the intention of Parliament&rdquo;.
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <CASEREF><SOC>Rizzo &amp; Rizzo Shoes Ltd. (Re)</SOC><CITE>[1998] 1 SCR 27</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1998] SCJ No 2</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> at &para;21, Factum of the Appellants, Appendix A, Tab 7.</P1></P>
<P>15. This modern approach to statutory interpretation is also reflected in the <EM>Interpretation Act</EM>, RSNL 1990, c 1&ndash;19, which provides:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>16.</N><TI>Rule of construction</TI><SECP>Every Act and every regulation and every provision of an Act or regulation shall be considered remedial and shall receive the liberal construction and interpretation that best ensures the attainment of the objects of the Act, regulation, or provision according to its true meaning.</SECP></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <EM>Interpretation Act</EM>, RSNL 1990, c 1&ndash;19, at s 16, Factum of the Appellants, Appendix B, Tab 13.</P1></P>
<P>16. The Town submits that the learned applications judge correctly concluded that the 1915 Act did not restrict the Appellants' claims to arbitration. As noted in the Decision, there is apparent incongruity between clause 15 of the 1915 agreement and section 14 of the 1915 Act, which provisions are replicated side by side for ease of reference below:
<TABLE>
<SGMLTBL>
<TBLBODY TBLWD="600">
<TBLCDEFS COLSEP="VSINGLE" HALIGN="LEFT" CHARPOS="75%" TOPSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCDEF COLWD="50" TBLUNITS="PERCENT">
<TBLCDEF COLWD="50" TBLUNITS="PERCENT">
</TBLCDEFS>
<TBLROWS ROWSEP="HSINGLE" VALIGN="TOP" LEFTSEP="VSINGLE">
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">Section 14. <BOLD><UNDER><EM>Nothing herein or in the Schedule [i.e., 1915 agreement] hereto</EM></UNDER></BOLD> in relation to the settlement of claims by arbitration <BOLD><UNDER><EM>shall be held or construed to prejudice or exclude the right of any claimant to institute an action in a Court of competent jurisdiction</EM></UNDER></BOLD> in respect to <BOLD><UNDER><EM>any</EM></UNDER></BOLD> such claim [emphasis added].</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">Clause 15. <BOLD><UNDER><EM>If the Company, in or by reason of the exercise of any rights hereby granted</EM></UNDER></BOLD>, submerge, destroy, damage or <BOLD><UNDER><EM>injuriously affect any private rights</EM></UNDER></BOLD>, interests, lands or property, and shall be unable to agree with the owner thereof as to compensation to be paid therefor, the Company, with the consent of the Governor in Council, may proceed with the exercise of the said rights, by these presents granted to the said Company, and the compensation to be paid by the Company to the owner, for or in respect to such rights, interests, lands or property, <BOLD><EM>shall be settled by arbitration in the manner hereinbefore provided</EM></BOLD> [emphasis added].</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
</TBLROWS>
</TBLBODY>
</SGMLTBL>
</TABLE>
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: Decision at &para;26, Appeal Book, Tab 3, p 16.</P1>
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: An Act for the Confirmation of a Contract with the Newfoundland Products Corporation Limited, Cap 4, 6 Geo v (1915), Factum of the Appellants, Appendix B, Tab 10 [1915 Act].</P1></P>
<P>17. While clause 15 of the 1915 agreement purports to mandate arbitration with respect to any dispute between the Company and private interests, the 1915 Act provides a residual right for a claimant to commence an action in the Court of competent jurisdiction. The interplay of these two seemingly conflicting provisions appears to provide potential claimants with the ability to elect the procedural vehicle in pursuing a dispute with the Company despite the provision for arbitration.
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: Decision at &para;&para;25-26, Appeal Book, Tab 3, p 16.</P1></P>
<P>18. The Town acknowledges that the Arbitration Clause in the 1923 Act is broad in its provision of arbitration. The 1923 Act is silent with respect to a residual right for a claimant to pursue litigation in lieu of arbitration, but it does not expressly repeal the 1915 Act. The Town agrees with the learned applications judge's conclusion that the 1923 Act and agreement does not amend or vary the rights of a claimant to initiate and purse a claim in Court as was provided in the 1915 Act.
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: Decision at &para;37, Appeal Book, Tab 3, p 19.</P1>
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: An Act Further to Amend the Act 6 George V(1915), Chapter Four, Entitled &ldquo;An Act for the Confirmation of a Contract with the Newfoundland Products Corporation, Limited&rdquo;, Cap 1, 14 Geo v (1923), Factum of the Appellants, Appendix B, Tab 11 [1923 Act].</P1></P>
<P>19. The Arbitration Clause in the 1927 Act expressly replaces the Arbitration Clause in the 1923 Act.
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: An Act for the Confirmation of an Agreement Between the Government and International Paper Company of Newfoundland, Limited&rdquo;, Cap 4, 28 Geo v (1927), Factum of the Appellants, Appendix B, Tab 12 [1927 Act].</P1></P>
<P>20. The 1927 Act, and more particularly the Arbitration Clause, does not expressly repeal or replace the 1915 agreement or the 1915 Act. Rather, section 2 of the 1927 Act adopts all &ldquo;rights, powers, privileges, franchises and exemptions vested in, or owned or enjoyed by the Old Company [Newfoundland Products Corporation, Limited] <UNDER><EM>under the Act and Agreement of 1915</EM></UNDER>...&rdquo; (emphasis added)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Tab 1 of the Applicant's Book of Authorities, p36.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>.
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <EM>1927 Act</EM>, Factum of the Appellants, Appendix B, Tab 12 at p 36.</P1></P>
<P>21. It follows that the residual right to litigate provided for in section 14 of the 1915 Act is in fact preserved insofar as the Arbitration Clause in the 1927 Act contemplates.</P>
<P>22. As noted above, the Arbitration Clause as set out in the 1927 Act provides:
<QUOTE><P><EM>(n) Clause 8 of the Agreement of 1923 shall not apply to the Company; but the following provision shall apply to the Company:</EM></P>
<P><EM>Any questions, disputes or differences between the parties hereto</EM>, <BOLD><EM>or between the Company and third parties where provision for arbitration is made herein</EM></BOLD>, <EM>or in the Act or Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements, arising out of, under or in connection with this Agreement or the Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements, or the execution thereof, shall on the application of either party by submitted to the arbitration of three arbitrators and the provisions of Part VI of the Judicature Act, Chapter 83 of the Consolidated Statutes (Third Series), except Section 212 and except as modified in this Clause, shall apply to any such submission. One arbitrator shall be appointed by each of the parties and the third by the two so appointed. If either party does not appoint an arbitrator within twenty days of the appointment of the second of such two, the Supreme Court or a Judge thereof may upon application be either party appoint such arbitrator or arbitrators. The award of the arbitrators or any two of them shall be final and binding upon the parties therefore, unless appeal therefrom shall be made to the Supreme Court and notice of such appeal shall be filed in the Registry of the Supreme Court within thirty days from the date of such award</EM>.</P>
<P><EM>[emphasis Added]</EM></P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <EM>1927 Act</EM>, Factum of the Appellants, Appendix B, Tab 12 at p 50.</P1></P>
<P>23. The applications judge erred in concluding that &ldquo;contrary to the position advanced by the Town, it would be unreasonable to exclude claims between the Company and third parties from the scope of this clause in view of the language of the provision&rdquo;. With respect, this is incorrect. The grammatical structure of the Arbitration Clause is significant as it provides for arbitration between the Company and third parties, such as the Appellants, only where provision for arbitration is made in the 1927 Act and agreement.
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: Decision at &para;43, Appeal Book, Tab 3, p 20.</P1></P>
<P>24. Specifically, the first component of the Arbitration Clause broadly states that any questions or disputes between the &ldquo;parties hereto&rdquo; of the 1927 agreement, being the Governor of Newfoundland and its Dependencies, in Council, and th e International Paper Company of Newfoundland, Limited, are to be submitted to arbitration on the application of either party. Notably, third parties, such as the Appellants, are not parties to the 1927 agreement.</P>
<P>25. The provision for arbitration with respect to disputes between the Company and third parties is more limited. The emphasized portion of the Arbitration Clause above is a disjunctive clause, separated on either end by commas, that provides for arbitration only where it is prescribed elsewhere in the 1927 Act and agreement.</P>
<P>26. In reviewing the Arbitration Clause, it is evident that the Legislature did not intend for the provision of arbitration to be the same between the parties as compared to the Company and third parties. The treatment for these two groups is distinct, which is reflected in the grammatical construction of the Arbitration Clause. The applications' judge was incorrect in finding that the scope of the Arbitration Clause applied equally to disputes between the Company and the Government and those between the Company and third parties.
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: Decision at &para;43, Appeal Book, Tab 3, p 20.</P1></P>
<P>27. Other than the Arbitration Clause, the 1927 Act only contemplates arbitration in two other instances, being clause 8 and 9(d). Clause 8 is not material to the within proceedings. It provides, as follows:
<QUOTE><P><EM>The Board of Railway Commissioners may enter into an agreement or agreements with the Company for furnishing to the Company and its subsidiaries all or any services over which the said Board now has or shall hereafter have jurisdiction at such rates and for such period and upon such terms and conditions, including provision for successive renewals and for the fixing</EM> <BOLD><EM>by arbitration</EM></BOLD> <EM>or otherwise of rates and other terms applicable to such renewals, as the said Board shall determine [emphasis added]</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <EM>1927 Act</EM>, Factum of the Appellants, Appendix B, Tab 12 at p 59.</P1></P>
<P>28. Clause 9(d) of the 1927 Act provides:
<QUOTE><P><EM>9. The Company may at any time or times do any or all of the following:</EM>
<P1>&ellipsis;</P1>
<P1><EM>(a) For the purpose of supplying water to the mills and other works of the Company and any towns in or near which the same are located, the Company may divert, stop or dam up and regulate the flow of such bodies of water as it may deem necessary or desirable and take and use such water and transmit the same by means of either natural or artificial channels or by other conduits; and made regulations for safeguarding such water supply from pollution, which regulations when approved by the Governor in Council shall have the force and effect of law;</EM> <BOLD><EM>provided that where the common law rights of riparian owners are affected thereby, compensation to be settled between the parties or by arbitration as provided thereunder, shall be made by the Company...</EM></BOLD> <EM>[emphasis added]</EM>.</P1></P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <EM>1927 Act</EM>, Factum of the Appellants, Appendix B, Tab 12 at p 61.</P1></P>
<P>29. The Appellants' claims, as set out in the Statement of Claim, are framed broadly in nuisance and negligence and do not expressly contemplate a breach of common law riparian rights.
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: Statement of Claim issued May 22, 2015, Appeal Book, Tab 4, p 26.</P1></P>
<P>30. The essential character of the Appellants' claims fall outside the scope of clause 9(d) of the 1927 Act that provides for the determination of compensation to be paid by the Company to common law riparian owners that are injuriously affected by the Company's activities by way of arbitration.</P>
<P>31. The Town submits that as the Appellants' claims are not captured in the subject matter of the mandatory arbitration provisions that are provided elsewhere in the 1927 Act and agreement, it follows that the dispute between the Company and the Appellants' are not caught by the Arbitration Clause and are not precluded from litigating the matter before the court of inherent jurisdiction, being the Supreme Court of Newfoundland and Labrador.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>The Proceeding should not be stayed against the Company</TI>
<P>32. The Town submits that the applications judge committed a further reviewable error in failing to exercise its discretion under the <EM>Arbitration Act</EM>, RSNL 1990, c A-14 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Arbitration Act&rdquo;</BOLD>), to refrain from staying the proceedings against the Company. In particular, the Decision is absent of any consideration of the provisions of the Arbitration Act, which is an error of law.</P>
<P>33. Section 4 of the Arbitration Act provides:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>4.</N><TI>Staying proceedings</TI><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>Where a party to a submission, or a person claiming through or under a party, begins legal proceedings against another party to the submission, or a person claiming through or under a party, in respect of a matter agreed to be referred, a party to the legal proceedings may, after appearance and before delivering pleadings or taking other steps in the proceedings, apply to the court for an order staying the proceedings.</SSECP></SSEC>
<SSEC><N>(2)</N><SSECP>The court may make an order staying the proceedings under subsection (1), upon being satisfied,
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>that there is no sufficient reason why the matter should not be referred to arbitration in accordance with the submission; and</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>that the applicant was, at the time the proceedings started, and still is ready and willing to do all things necessary for the proper conduct of the arbitration.</PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></SEC>
<P>[emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <EM>Arbitration Act</EM>, RSNL 1990, c A-14, at s 4, Tab 5.</P1></P>
<P>34. Unlike the comparable legislation in other jurisdictions, the Arbitration Act in this Province provides a residual discretion for the Court to refrain from staying proceedings and referring a matter to arbitration (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Judicial Discretion Provision&rdquo;</BOLD>).</P>
<P>35. The Judicial Discretion Provision has been part of arbitration legislation in this Province since 1916 and has remained largely unchanged since that time. The first iteration of the Judicial Discretion Provision is found in Part VI of the <EM>Judicature Act</EM>, c 83 of the Consolidated Statutes (Third Series) (the <BOLD>&ldquo;1916 Judicature Act&rdquo;</BOLD>), which provides:
<QUOTE><P><EM>195. If any party to a submission, or any person claiming through or under him, commences any legal proceedings against any other party to the submission, or any person claiming through or under him, in respect of any matter agreed to be referred, any party to such legal proceedings may at any time after appearance, and before delivering any pleadings or taking any other steps in the proceedings, apply to the Court to stay proceedings, and the Court or a Judge thereof, if satisfied that there is no sufficient reason why the matter should not be referred in accordance with the submission, and that the applicant was, at the time when the proceedings were commenced, and still remains, ready and willing to do all things necessary to the proper conduct of the arbitration, may make an order staying the proceedings. [emphasis added]</EM></P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <EM>Judicature Act</EM>, c 83 of the Consolidated Statutes (Third Series), at s 195, Tab 7 [<EM>1916 Judicature Act</EM>].</P1></P>
<P>36. The term &ldquo;submission&rdquo; is defined in the 1916 Judicature Act as a &ldquo;written agreement to submit present or future differences to arbitration, whether an arbitrator is named therein or not&rdquo;.
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <EM>1916 Judicature Act</EM>, at s 214, Tab 7.</P1></P>
<P>37. The Arbitration Clause in the 1927 Act also refers to the 1916 Judicature Act with respect to the procedure to be followed upon reference to arbitration:
<QUOTE><P><EM>Any questions, disputes or differences between the parties hereto, or between the Company and third parties where provision for arbitration is made herein, or in the Act or Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements, arising out of, under or in connection with this Agreement or the Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements, or the execution thereof, shall on the application of either party by submitted to the arbitration of three arbitrators</EM> <BOLD><EM>and the provisions of Part VI of the Judicature Act, Chapter 83 of the Consolidated Statutes (Third Series), except Section 212 and except as modified in this Clause, shall apply to any such submission</EM></BOLD>. <EM>One arbitrator shall be appointed by each of the parties and the third by the two so appointed. If either party does not appoint an arbitrator within twenty days of the appointment of the second of such two, the Supreme Court or a Judge thereof may upon application be either party appoint such arbitrator or arbitrators. The award of the arbitrators or any tow of them shall be final and binding upon the parties therefore, unless appeal therefrom shall be made to the Supreme Court and notice of such appeal shall be filed in the Registry of the Supreme Court within thirty days from the date of such award. [emphasis added]</EM></P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <EM>1927 Act</EM>, Factum of the Appellants, Appendix B, Tab 12 at p 50.</P1></P>
<P>38. Notably, the Arbitration Clause does not override the judicial discretion provided for in section 195 of the 1916 Judicature Act.</P>
<P>39. The Judicial Discretion Provision continued to be housed in the subsequent iterations of the 1916 Judicature Act until 1984, at which time the statute underwent significant amendments. Specifically, the <EM>Judicature Act, 1984</EM>, no longer included provisions with respect to the procedures for the conduct of arbitration. Instead, these provisions, including the Judicial Discretion Provision, were enacted in the <EM>Arbitration Act</EM> in 1985. The Judicial Discretion Provision has continued in substance since that time.
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <EM>The Judicature Act, 1984</EM>, SNL 1984, c 25, Tab 9.</P1>
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <EM>The Arbitration Act</EM>, SNL 1985, c 8, at s 4, Tab 8.</P1></P>
<P>40. It follows that Legislature has clearly contemplated a residual judicial discretion to refrain from a stay of proceedings for arbitration since 1916, which was in force at the time of the enactment of the 1927 Act and agreement.</P>
<P>41. The Town agrees with the application judge's decision that Canadian courts have largely affirmed arbitrators' jurisdiction and stayed proceedings in favour of arbitration; however, the applications judge erred in failing to distinguish these decisions in the circumstances in light of the Judicial Discretion Provision that is unique to our Arbitration Act.
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: Decision at &para;52, Appeal Book, Tab 3, p 22.</P1></P>
<P>42. For instance, the Decision relies on <CASEREF><SOC>Weber v Ontario Hydro</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Weber v Ontario Hydro</SOC><CITE>[1995] 2 SCR 929</CITE></CASEREF> [<EM>Weber</EM>], at Tab 7</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> as a leading case to illustrate the Supreme Court of Canada's articulation of an arbitrator's exclusive jurisdiction over all aspects of a dispute in matters where the Legislature had directed matters to be resolved by way of arbitration.
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: Decision at &para;&para;52, 57, Appeal Book, Tab 3, pp 22, 24.</P1>
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <CASEREF><SOC>Weber v Ontario Hydro</SOC><CITE>[1995] 2 SCR 929</CITE></CASEREF>, Tab 3 [<EM>Weber</EM>].</P1></P>
<P>43. At the time the <EM>Weber</EM> case was decided, the Ontario <EM>Arbitration Act, 1991</EM>, SO 1991, c 17, provided:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>7.</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><TI>Stay</TI><SSECP>If a party to an arbitration agreement commences a proceeding in respect of a matter to be submitted to arbitration under the agreement, the court in which the proceeding is commenced shall, on the motion of another party to the arbitration agreement, stay the proceeding.</SSECP></SSEC>
<SSEC><N>(2)</N><SSECP>Exceptions However, the court may refuse to stay the proceeding in any of the following cases:
<PARA><N>1.</N><PARAP>A party entered into the arbitration agreement while under a legal incapacity.</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>2.</N><PARAP>The arbitration agreement is invalid.</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>3.</N><PARAP>The subject-matter of the dispute is not capable of being the subject of arbitration under Ontario law.</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>4.</N><PARAP>The motion was brought with undue delay.</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>5.</N><PARAP>The matter is a proper one for default or summary judgment.</PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></SEC>
<P><EM>[emphasis added]</EM></P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: Arbitration Act, 1991, SO 1991, c 17, at s 7, Tab 6.</P1></P>
<P>44. It is evident that the Ontario legislation in force at that time provided limited circumstances where the Court could refrain from ordering a stay of proceedings. Unlike the Judicial Discretion Provision, section 7 of the Ontario <EM>Arbitration Act, 1991</EM>, suggests the Ontario legislature intended for arbitration to be enforced in all but very specific circumstances. The applications judge, in failing to distinguish the Ontario legislation, incorrectly applied the law.</P>
<P>45. In comparison, Courts in this jurisdiction have considered the Judicial Discretion Provision when refraining to order a stay of proceedings. In <CASEREF><SOC>Hurley v Slate Ventures Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, Green J. (as he then was) refused to order a stay of proceedings where a shareholders' agreement mandating arbitration only pertained to certain aspects of the content of the litigation. The Plaintiff shareholder had commenced a legal action but then requested a stay of proceedings for the aspects of the litigation that were contemplated in the arbitration provision. Green J. refused, stating:
<QUOTE><P><EM>[47] ... Some of the issues and certainly much of the evidence will overlap the matters properly referable to arbitration under the agreement. Unless the matters are easily severable and can be discreetly compartmentalized, it would not be appropriate to delay court proceedings to enable an arbitration of some of the issues to be dealt with, especially where issues dealt with in the arbitration might also have been canvassed in the subsequent court proceedings, albeit from a different point of view. Here, the matters are intertwined. It is not sufficient for Hurley to say that he would agree to be bound by any findings of fact made at the arbitration. Evidence relating to the events in dispute would have to be covered again and may be presented differently. One cannot say in advance what the findings at the arbitration might be or how they will impact on the issues that will ultimately be before the court. The possibility of conflicting findings remain</EM>.</P>
<P><EM>[48] Additionally, it is important that all outstanding issues between the parties be resolved in a timely manner. A bifurcation of the dispute between arbitration and court proceedings will only have the potential of lengthening the resolution</EM>.</P>
<P><EM>[49] Traditional principles applicable to determine when a court will not insist that a matter proceed to arbitration</EM>, <BOLD><EM>even though the parties have agreed to such a course, recognize that although as a general rule the court ought to allow the issue to be settled in the agreed upon forum the court nevertheless retains a discretion to order that the issues not go to arbitration in appropriate cases</EM></BOLD> <EM>[three references in Newfoundland and Labrador and Prince Edward Island cases]. Here, where all the issues raised by Hurley cannot be resolved by arbitration and where the issues that could be referred to arbitration arising out of &ldquo;any matter or thing concerning or relating to [the] agreement&rdquo; are essentially ones of law relating to the construction of the agreement, I believe it makes sense that the court should not defer to the request of the Plaintiff and should deny the reference to arbitration [emphasis added]</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <CASEREF><SOC>Hurley v Slate Ventures Inc.</SOC><YEAR>1996</YEAR><CITE>136 Nfld &amp; PEIR 341</CITE><COURTJUR>NLTD</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at &para;&para; 47&ndash;49, Tab 1 [<EM>Hurley</EM>].</P1></P>
<P>46. Similar to the litigation in <EM>Hurley</EM>, the within proceedings cannot be arbitrated in its entirety as only the Appellants and the Company would be party to arbitration, if it is ordered.</P>
<P>47. In <CASEREF><SOC>Marine Atlantic Inc. v Seabase Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, Hickman C.J. adopted the following criteria for determining whether a dispute should be resolved under the provisions of an arbitration clause or whether the Court should assume jurisdiction and determine the rights of the parties:
<QUOTE><P><EM>1. If the agreement for arbitration covers the claim as set out in the pleadings, it is the prima facie duty of the court to allow the issue to be settled in the agreed upon forum, and to grant the stay of proceedings;</EM></P>
<P><EM>2. The onus lies upon him who opposes the stay to satisfy the court that there is sufficient reason why the matter should be proceeded with in that agreed forum;</EM></P>
<P><EM>3. It is incumbent upon the court at this stage to inquire into the merits of the issue or issues but it must first determine:</EM></P>
<P><EM>(a) the precise nature of the issues between the parties;</EM></P>
<P><EM>(b) whether or not those issues fall within the terms of the arbitration clause;</EM></P>
<P><EM>(c) whether the arbitration clause is still operative;</EM></P>
<P><EM>4. the court may consider that sufficient reason exists why the issues should not go to arbitration</EM></P>
<P><EM>(a) if the questions to be determined are ones of law, or relating to the construction of the agreement, or of a complexity of mixed fact and law</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <CASEREF><SOC>Marine Atlantic Inc. v Seabase Ltd</SOC><YEAR>1995</YEAR><CITE>132 Nfld &amp; PEIR 121</CITE><COURTJUR>NLTD</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at &para;20, Tab 2 [<EM>Marine Atlantic</EM>].</P1></P>
<P>48. Hickman, C.J.'s comments in <EM>Marine Atlantic</EM> were cited with approval by Butler J. in <CASEREF><SOC>Wheeler v Hwang</SOC></CASEREF> as the onus is on the contesting party to demonstrate why the matter ought not to proceed to arbitration.
<P1><UNDER>Reference</UNDER>: <CASEREF><SOC>Wheeler v Hwang</SOC><CITE>2007 NLTD 145</CITE><PARANUM>15</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Tab 4.</P1></P>
<P>49. In the present case, the interests of justice would not be best served in ordering a stay of proceedings. The bifurcation of proceedings between a court action and arbitration may lead to different factual findings and are also not an optimal use of judicial resources. The Town submits that the applications judge committed a reviewable error in failing to exercise his discretion to stay the proceedings.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;ORDER OR RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P>50. The Town requests that this Court answer the issues raised on this appeal as follows:</P>
<P>51. The standard of review on the questions before this Court is correctness.
<P1>(a) Issue 1: The applications judge erred in concluding that the Arbitration Clause in the 1927 Act required the Appellants to refer their claims against the Company to arbitration.</P1>
<P1>(b) Issue 2: The applications judge erred in declining to exercise discretion to dismiss the Jurisdiction Application.</P1></P>
<P>52. The Town therefore seeks that the appeal be dismissed.</P>
