<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;Overview</TI>
<P>1. The Appellants appeal a decision of the applications judge granting an application by Corner Brook Pulp and Paper Company (the &ldquo;Company&rdquo;) to stay the Appellants' action against the Company pending arbitration of the Appellants' claim with the Company. The appeal raises issues of the proper interpretation of arbitration provisions contained in historic legislation. The appeal also engages the alternate argument of a review of a discretionary decision of the applications judge to not stay the action against the Company.</P>
<P>2. The Province argues that the applications judge erred in his interpretation of the arbitration clauses and that the relevant legislation does not operate to bar the claims made by the Appellants against the Company.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;Concise Statement of Facts</TI>
<P>3. The Appellants issued a statement of claim wherein they allege that flooding has caused water damage to their properties. As against the Company, the Appellants seek damages for interference with their property rights in nuisance and negligence.</P>
<P>4. The Company brought an application seeking to have the claim as against them stayed (the &ldquo;Stay Application&rdquo;). The Company alleges the action is barred by certain arbitration provisions contained within the legislation and agreements outlined below:
<P1>&bull; <EM>An Act for the Confirmation of an Agreement Between the Government and International Paper Company of Newfoundland, Limited</EM> (the &ldquo;1927 Act&rdquo;) and the attached Schedule (the &ldquo;1927 Agreement&rdquo;);
<P2><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, Appendix B, Tab 12</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>&bull; <EM>An Act to Amend the Act 6 George V. (1915), Chapter Four, Entitled &ldquo;An Act for the Confirmation of a Contract with the Newfoundland Products Corporation, Limited&rdquo;</EM> (the &ldquo;1923 Act&rdquo;) and Part II of the Schedule to the 1923 Act (the &ldquo;1923 Agreement&rdquo;); and,
<P2><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, Appendix B, Tab 11</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>&bull; <EM>An Act for the Confirmation of a Contract with the Newfoundland Products Corporation</EM> (the &ldquo;1915 Act&rdquo;) and the attached Schedule (the &ldquo;1915 Agreement&rdquo;).
<P2><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, Appendix B, Tab 10</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>5. The applications judge concluded that under the 1915 Act a claimant had the right to pursue a claim in Court and was not restricted to arbitration and that this right was not amended or varied by the 1923 Agreement.
<P1><BOLD>Applications Judge's Decision at paras 14&ndash;26 and para 37, Appeal Book, Tab 3</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>6. The applications judge determined that the 1927 Agreement &ldquo;effectively take[s] away the right to litigate a claim in Court in favour of mandatory arbitration.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>Applications Judge's Decision at para 42, Appeal Book, Tab 3</BOLD></P1></P>
<P><BOLD>7.</BOLD> The applications judge found that neither the Appellants, the Town, nor the Province established that the Court should not follow the legislation which mandated arbitration.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;Issues</TI>
<P>8. The following are submitted as the issues relevant to determine this appeal:
<P1>(1) Is there a provision for mandatory arbitration in an act or agreement that prohibits the Appellants' action against the Company?</P1>
<P1>(2) Did the applications judge err in declining to exercise discretion to deny the Stay Application?</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">Part IV Argument</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>Standard of Review</TI>
<P>9. The Province agrees with the Appellants' submissions as to the standard of review applicable to this appeal. The Province agrees that the standard applicable to Issue 1 is correctness and that Issue 2 involves the exercise of discretion of the Applications Judge and therefore the standard of review is palpable and overriding error, unless the error amounted to an error of law, which would be subject to a standard of correctness.</P>
<BLOCK4 LABEL="Issue"><N>1</N><TI>Is there a provision for mandatory arbitration in an act or agreement that prohibits the Appellants' action against the Company?</TI>
<P>10. It is respectfully submitted that the applications judge was incorrect in his determination that the 1927 legislation requires mandatory arbitration of the Appellants' claim against the Company.</P>
<P>11. Under the modern approach to statutory interpretation, it is well established that the &ldquo;words of an Act are to be read in their entire context and in their grammatical and ordinary sense harmoniously with the scheme of the Act, the object of the Act, and the intention of Parliament&rdquo;. In addition, the provincial legislature has provided that statutes must generally receive the liberal construction and interpretation that best ensures the attainment of the objects of the Act or provision according to its true meaning.</P>
<P>12. In order to interpret the arbitration clause, it must be read in context, including the immediate context of the language of the relevant section and the statute as a whole, and its intended meaning gleaned within that context. The text of the provision must be read harmoniously with the context and purpose of the statute.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Penney v. Newfoundland and Labrador</SOC><CITE>2017 NLCA 25</CITE><PARANUM>17-18</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>First Respondents Factum, Tab 4</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>13. In order to determine whether the Appellants' claim should be stayed, the Court must first interpret the arbitration provisions and then analyse the Appellants' claim to determine whether that claim must be decided by an arbitrator under the terms of the agreement, as interpreted by the Court.</P>
<P>14. Clause 2(n) of the 1927 Agreement appended to the 1927 Act is the relevant arbitration Clause 2(n) provides as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Clause 8 of the Agreement of 1923 shall not apply to the Company: but the following provision shall apply to the Company:
<QUOTE><P>Any questions, disputes or differences between the parties hereto, or between the Company and third parties where provision for arbitration is made herein, or in the Act or Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements, arising out of, under or in connection with this Agreement or the Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements, or the execution thereof, shall on the application of either party be submitted to the arbitration of three arbitrators and the provisions of Part VI. of the Judicature Act, Chapter 83 of the Consolidated Statutes (Third Series), except Section 212 and except as modified in this Clause, shall apply to any such submission. (...)</P></QUOTE></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, Appendix B, Tab 12</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>15. The opening wording of clause 2 of the 1927 Agreement confirms the rights enjoyed and the obligations imposed by the 1915 legislation and agreements and subsequent acts and agreements, except as modified or otherwise affected by the 1927 legislation. The 1927 legislation specifically amended the arbitration provision in the 1923 Agreement.</P>
<P>16. As a result of the 1927 amendment, in relation to disputes between the Company and third parties, clause 2(n) mandates that arbitration <UNDER>only applies</UNDER> &ldquo;...where provision for arbitration is made herein [the 1927 legislation], or in the Act or Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements...&rdquo;. Therefore, to determine whether the Appellants claims against the Company are captured by mandatory arbitration it is necessary to consider where provision for arbitration is made in relation to disputes between the Company and third parties in the relevant acts and agreements.</P>
<BLOCK5><TI><UNDER>Arbitration Clauses</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK6><TI>&bull; 1927 Act and Agreement</TI>
<P>17. Aside from clause 2(n), the only arbitration provisions applicable to third parties within the 1927 legislation are found in clause 8 and clause 9(d) of the 1927 Agreement.</P>
<P>18. Clause 8 is not material as it is specific to disputes between the Company and the Board of Railway Commissioners.
<P1><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, Appendix B, Tab 12</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>19. Clause 9(d) provides the Company with rights to dam up and regulate the flow of certain water
<QUOTE><P>...;provided that where the common law rights of riparian owners are affected thereby, compensation to be settled between the parties or by arbitration as provided hereunder, shall be made by the Company.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, Appendix B, Tab 12</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>20. Pursuant to clause 9(d) of the 1927 legislation, when the common law riparian rights of third parties are affected by the Company's actions, if the third party and the Company cannot reach a settlement agreement on the compensation to be paid, then the question of compensation is to be settled by arbitration.</P>
<P>21. The Appellants' claim does not allege that they are riparian owners and the Appellants are not seeking compensation for the Company's interference with the common law rights of riparian owners. Therefore, it is submitted that clause 9(d) is not applicable to the within proposed class proceeding and therefore does not mandate arbitration between the Appellants and the Company.</P>
<P>22. Further, it is submitted that even if the Appellants' claim was based on common law riparian rights, the language of clause 9(d) requires that there be no dispute that it was the Company that affected the common law rights of the third parties. The arbitration provision referenced in clause 9(d) is only triggered &ldquo;where the common law rights of riparian owners <BOLD><UNDER>are affected thereby</UNDER></BOLD>&rdquo;. That is, where the third party's common law riparian rights are affected by the Company exercising its rights to, among other things, dam up and regulate the flow of water. It is submitted that the arbitration clause is operative only when there is not a dispute as to the Company's liability but there is a dispute as to the compensation payable for the Company's interference with these riparian rights. The arbitration is not to adjudicate whether or not the Company caused interference with such rights. The legislation only confers jurisdiction on the arbitrators to determine compensation, not liability.</P></BLOCK6>
<BLOCK6><TI>&bull; 1923 Act and Agreement</TI>
<P>23. There is no arbitration provision within the 1923 Act that refers to arbitration with third parties.</P>
<P>24. Clause 8 of the 1923 Agreement outlines an arbitration process in relation to &ldquo;[a]ny questions, disputes or differences arising out of, under or in connection with this Agreement or the execution thereof...&rdquo;. By application, &ldquo;either party&rdquo; can trigger this arbitration process. There is no reference to third parties in this provision. The parties to the agreement are the Governor of Newfoundland and the Newfoundland Power and Paper Company, Limited.
<P1><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, Appendix B, Tab 11</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>25. It is submitted that the provisions of the 1923 legislation do not mandate arbitration between the Appellants and the Company.</P></BLOCK6>
<BLOCK6><TI>&bull; 1915 Act and Agreement</TI>
<P>26. It is a matter of debate to what extent the 1927 Act and/or the 1923 Act amended or replaced the 1915 Act and the 1915 Agreement. However, it is submitted that regardless of the position, nothing in the 1915 Act or Agreement mandates arbitration for the Appellants' claim against the Company.</P></BLOCK6>
<BLOCK6><TI>&bull; 1915 Agreement</TI>
<P>27. Clause 2 of the 1915 Agreement provides that in the event that the dams built by the Company become a benefit for other companies, then the other companies shall pay a proportionate cost of maintenance and operations. If the amount payable cannot be agreed upon, then the amount shall be determined by arbitration in the manner provided. This clause is not relevant to the Appellants' claim.
<P1><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, Appendix B, Tab 10</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>28. Similarly, clause 3 of the 1915 Agreement requires the Company to furnish electrical power to third parties in Labrador at a price to be agreed upon. Failing agreement, the amount is to be settled by arbitration. Clause 3 sets out the procedure for arbitration related to such disputes. Clause 3 is not relevant to the Appellants' claim.
<P1><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, Appendix B, Tab 10</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>29. Clause 10 of the 1915 Agreement provides the Company, with the consent of Government, the power to expropriate certain lands that the Company may require. Clause 10 sets out a different procedure for arbitration than the procedure contemplated in clause 3 of the 1915 Agreement. To determine compensation payable to the third parties, clause 10 requires arbitration in the manner provided by section 55 of the <EM>Lands Act</EM>. This clause is not relevant to the Appellants' claim.
<P1><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, Appendix B, Tab 10</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>30. Clause 15 of the 1915 Agreement states the following:
<QUOTE><P>If the Company, in or by reason of the exercise of any of the rights hereby granted, submerge, destroy, damage or injuriously affect any private rights, interests, lands or property, and shall be unable to agree with the owner thereof as to compensation to be paid therefor, the Company, with the consent of the Governor in Council, may proceed with the exercise of the said rights, by these presents granted to the said Company, and the compensation to be paid by the Company to the owner, for or in respect to such rights, interests, lands or property, shall be settled by arbitration in the manner hereinbefore provided.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, Appendix B, Tab 10</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>31. Similar to clause 9(d) of the 1927 legislation, the Province submits that this provision is inoperative in relation to disputes about liability. Clause 15 contemplates arbitration in circumstances when the Company has accepted liability but is unable to agree with the owner as to the compensation to be paid. In the scenario contemplated by this provision, arbitration is not triggered until the Company has tried and failed to negotiate compensation with the private owner. In this provision the arbitrators are given jurisdiction to settle an amount owing to the third parties, however, the arbitrators are not given jurisdiction to determine liability.</P></BLOCK6>
<BLOCK6><TI>&bull; 1915 Act</TI>
<P>32. The 1915 Act &ldquo;approved and confirmed, subject to the conditions and exceptions hereinafter contained&rdquo; the 1915 Agreement attached as a Schedule to the 1915 Act. As such, any changes in the 1915 Act amend the 1915 Agreement.
<P1><BOLD>Section 1, 1915 Act, Appellants' Factum, Appendix B, Tab 10</BOLD></P1></P>
<P><BOLD>33.</BOLD> Section 13 of the 1915 Act amends the arbitration procedure referred to in clause 10 of the 1915 Agreement. This applies to situations where the Company has expropriated land and arbitration is required to settle the amount of compensation.</P>
<P>34. Section 14 of the 1915 Act states
<QUOTE><P>Nothing herein or in the Schedule hereto in relation to the settlement of claims by arbitration shall be held or construed to prejudice or exclude the right of any claimant to institute an action in a Court of competent jurisdiction in respect to any such claim.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Appellants' Factum, Appendix B, Tab 10</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>35. Section 14 confirms that the arbitration provision does not preclude court action. Indeed, section 14 of the legislation is logical in light of clause 15 of the agreement as clause 15 only operates when liability is not in dispute. In situations where liability is an issue, the legislation confirms that litigation is an appropriate and permissible recourse.</P>
<P>36. Furthermore, there has been no amendment to section 14 in subsequent agreements or legislation, nor has there been a separate clause that would override this provision. Section 14 is a clear statement that the arbitration processes outlined in the legislation and agreements do not preclude court action.</P>
<P>37. Section 19 of the 1915 Act refers to arbitration when the Company's actions cause any material depreciation in the capacity for development of a water power owned by the holder of a grant, license or lease to cut timber. The Appellants' claim does not involve the development of a water power, therefore, this provision is not applicable.</P>
<P>38. The Province submits that clause 2(n), when read in the context of the agreements as a whole, means that all disputes between the Province and the Company are subject to arbitration, and that in relation to disputes between the Company and third parties, arbitration is mandatory only &ldquo;...where provision for arbitration is made herein [in the 1927 legislation] or in the Act or Agreement of 1915 or any of the Subsequent Acts and Agreements...&rdquo;.</P>
<P>39. The consideration of the phrase &ldquo;where provision for arbitration is made herein...&rdquo; is necessary to properly interpret the intended scope of arbitration between the Company and third parties. The rejection of the phrase is permissible only if it is otherwise impossible to reconcile or give effect to the Act.</P>
<P>40. Each provision of an act is presumed to have a role to play in the overall scheme. An interpretation of one provision that makes another redundant or that conflicts with other provisions strongly indicates that the legislature intended the provision be interpreted differently.
<P1><EM>Statutory Interpretation</EM>, Sullivan R. (3<SUP>rd</SUP> ed. 2016) at pp 173&ndash;179., Tab 1</P1></P>
<P>41. If you accept the Company's theory that all disputes must be referred to arbitration regardless if the dispute is between the Company and the Province, or if the dispute is between the Company and third parties, then what meaning is given to &ldquo;where provision for arbitration is made herein&rdquo;? Under the Company's theory, this phrase becomes superfluous, which is contrary to the established principles of statutory interpretation.</P>
<P>42. Clause 8 of the 1923 legislation provides that all issues between the parties are to be arbitrated. That was modified by clause 2(n) in the 1927 legislation to say that all disputes between the parties are to be arbitrated, and those disputes between the Company and third parties, where provision is made, are to be arbitrated.</P>
<P>43. As noted above, arbitration between the Company and third parties is mandated only in the following circumstances:
<TABLE>
<SGMLTBL>
<TBLBODY TBLWD="600">
<TBLCDEFS COLSEP="VSINGLE" HALIGN="LEFT" CHARPOS="75%" TOPSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCDEF COLWD="18" TBLUNITS="PERCENT">
<TBLCDEF COLWD="16" TBLUNITS="PERCENT">
<TBLCDEF COLWD="66" TBLUNITS="PERCENT">
</TBLCDEFS>
<TBLROWS ROWSEP="HSINGLE" VALIGN="TOP" LEFTSEP="VSINGLE">
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">1915 Agreement</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">clause 2</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="3">Arbitration if Company's dams benefit third party companies and compensation cannot be agreed.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1"></TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">clause 3</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="3">Arbitration if Company furnishes electricity to third parties in Labrador and parties cannot agree on compensation.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1"></TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">clause 10</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="3">Arbitration if Company expropriates third party land and compensation cannot be agreed.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1"></TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">clause 15</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="3">Arbitration if Company damages third party rights, interests, lands or property and compensation cannot be agreed.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">1915 Act</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">section 13</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="3">Amends arbitration procedure of clause 10 of the 1915 Agreement.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1"></TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">section 14</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="3">Confirms that nothing in the 1915 Act or Agreement shall be construed to prejudice or exclude the right of any claimant to institute an action in a Court of competent</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1"></TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">section 19</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="3">Arbitration if Company's actions affect third parties capacity for development of water power and the parties cannot agree on compensation.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">1923 Agreement</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">clause 8</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="3">Arbitration if there is a dispute between the parties to the agreement.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">1927 Agreement</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">clause 8</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="3">Arbitration or otherwise to determine rates and terms of service between the Company and the Board of Railway Commissioners.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1"></TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">clause 9(d)</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="3">Arbitration if Company affects common law rights of riparian owners and compensation cannot be agreed.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
</TBLROWS>
</TBLBODY>
</SGMLTBL>
</TABLE>
</P>
<P>44. In interpreting a statutory provision, one must look at the legislative context- that is, how the provision fits in and functions in the statutory scheme when considered together with other provisions.</P>
<P>45. Read as a whole, and considering how clause 2(n) fits in and functions in the statutory scheme, it is apparent that all of the arbitration provisions that apply to the Company and third parties deal with circumstances where an arbitrator would deal with a determination of quantum only. This interpretation forms and supports an internally consistent framework. The scheme of the acts and agreements is to provide arbitration in certain enumerated situations where the service or the liability is not in dispute, but the Company and the third party cannot agree as to the amount to be paid.</P>
<P>46. The Province submits that the subject matter of the Appellants' claim does not fall into any category of provision requiring arbitration in any of the relevant acts or agreements. Therefore, the Appellant's claim against the Company is not subject to clause 2(n) and the applications judge should not have allowed the Company's Stay Application.</P></BLOCK6></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4 LABEL="Issue"><N>2</N><TI>Did the Applications Judge err in declining to exercise discretion to deny the Stay Application?</TI>
<P>47. The Province adopts the argument set out in the Town's Factum with respect to the applications judge's error in failing to consider and exercise his discretionary power to refrain from staying the proceedings against the Company.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">Part V&mdash;Order or Relief Sought</TI>
<P>48. The Province respectfully requests that the applications judge's decision be set aside and that the Company's application for a stay be dismissed.</P>
<P>All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
